{{short description|xxx}}
{{use dmy dates|date=August 2021}}
{{Use British English|date=August 2021}}

[[File:A view of Truxillo, a city belonging to the Spaniards in the Bay of Honduras LCCN2003666724.jpg|thumb|upright=2|alt=A view of Truxillo, a city belonging to the Spaniards in the Bay of Honduras (engraving for 1768 ''Voyages'' by E. C. Drake)|A view of Truxillo, a city belonging to the Spaniards in the Bay of Honduras (engraving for 1768 ''Voyages'' by E. C. Drake)]]

This is a timeline of the [[English settlement in the Bay of Honduras]], predecessor state to [[British Honduras]] and [[Belize]], from the 1630s to the 1860s.

== Prelude ==

=== 1600s ===

'''1600'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Outbreak of [[smallpox]] in [[Chiapas]], [[Verapaz, Guatemala|Verapaz]], and (possibly) the southern extreme of the district or {{lang|es|municipio}} of [[Bacalar]].{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=317, 333}}

'''1603'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Friars ''Esguerra'' and ''Cipriano'' (forcibly) resettle [[Manche Ch'ol]] residents of Verapaz or the district of Bacalar during a {{lang|es|reducción}}.{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=18}}

'''1604'''
* 7 March{{snd}}7 March: Esteban de Alvarado and Carlos Vásquez de Coronado establish [[Santo Tomás de Castilla|Santo Tomas de Castilla]].{{sfn|Fuentes y Guzmán|1933|pp=301-302}}{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|p=823}}{{sfn|Zamora Castellanos|1941|pp=176-177}}{{sfn|Rodríguez del Valle|1960|pp=19–20}}{{sfn|Andrews|1978|pp=24–25}}

'''1607'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Dutch pirates or privateers, aboard eight {{lang|es|urcas}}, raid or attack Santo Tomas de Castilla and [[Puerto Cortés|Puerto Caballos]].{{sfn|Fuentes y Guzmán|1933|pp=307–308}}{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=108, 472}}{{sfn|Zamora Castellanos|1941|p=177}}

'''1608'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': {{lang|es|Reducciones}} take place near [[Tipu, Belize|Tipu]].{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=207}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=18, 132}}

=== 1610s ===

'''1610'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Dutch pirates or privateers, aboard twelve {{lang|es|urcas}}, raid or attack Puerto Caballos.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|p=108}}

'''1613'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates or privateers raid or attack [[Trujillo, Honduras|Truxillo]], during which they engage Antonio de Cerpa.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|p=108}}

'''1615'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Juan Sánchez de Aguilar, {{lang|es|alcalde ordinario}} of [[Bacalar]], (forcibly) relocates Mayan residents in the {{lang|es|villa}}'s district to the {{lang|es|reducción}} towns of Petentzub and Zaczuz.{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=132, 192–193}}<ref group=note>In 1622 (''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.''), {{lang|myn|Petentzub}}, {{lang|myn|Zaczuz}}, and other {{lang|es|reducción}} towns near [[Tipu, Belize|Tipu]] were reorganised as a new {{lang|es|encomienda}} of 136 {{lang|es|casados}} {{harv|Jones|1989|pp=???}}.</ref>

'''1616'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': English pirate or privateer, ''Quinn'', seeks to start settlement in [[Providence Island colony|Providence Island]].{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=51–53}}<ref group=note>During 1616{{snd}}1620, ''Quinn'' introduces [[cooking bananas|platains]], pineapples, [[cassava]], maize, cattle, pigs, hens to Providence, and cruises the [[Yucatan Channel]] {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=52}}. In the first quarter of 1629, [[Daniel Elfrith]] and [[Sussex Camock]] land on [[San Andrés (island)|Henrietta]] {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=57}}. On 24 December 1629, Elfrith lands on Providence {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=60}}.</ref>

'''1617'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': English pirates or privateers raid Bacalar, abducting five {{lang|es|vecinos}} of the {{lang|es|villa}}, including Pedro Rojo and Antonio Gómez.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=320|loc=item no. 19}}

'''1618'''
* 15 April{{snd}}8 December: [[Franciscans|Franciscan]] [[Friars|frairs]] Juan de Orbita and Bartolomé de Fuensalida are well-received by Mayan residents of the district of Bacalar while on a {{lang|es|misión}} to the [[Peten Itza kingdom]].{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|loc=''lib.'' 9 ''cap.'' 4—13}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=135–148}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|pp=240–244}}<ref group=note>{{lang|es|Misión}} participants included Juan de Acevedo, Gonzalo de Salazar, Gregorio Marín de Aguilar, Andrés Carillo de Pernia, Cristóbal Na, Isabel Pech, and Francisco Cumux (cf previous citations).</ref>
* 23 May{{snd}}15 May of 1648: [[Thirty Years' war]].

'''1619'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Franciscan friars Juan de Orbita and Bartolomé de Fuensalida are (again) well-received by Mayan residents of the district of Bacalar while on a {{lang|es|misión}} to the [[Peten Itza kingdom]].{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=244}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=18–19, 148–149}}

=== 1620s ===

'''1620'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Juan Alonso Díaz de Aguilar, {{lang|es|alcalde ordinario}} of [[Bacalar]], conducts a general {{lang|es|visita}} of the {{lang|es|villa}}'s district.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=193}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Friar Gabriel de Salazar circumnavigates the [[Yucatan peninsula]].{{sfn|Aliphat Fernández|Caso Barrera|2013|pp=853–856}}<ref group=note>Map by Fray lost /v Aliphat 854</ref>
* 29 February{{snd}}29 February: The 1580{{snds}}1581 prohibition of [[logwood]] imports into [[Kingdom of England|England]] is loosened to allow licensed importation, with Thomas Compton receiving the first such licence.{{sfn|Socolow|1996|p=478}}<ref group="note">The use of logwood dyes in England was prohibited sometime during 21 March 1580{{snd}}20 March 1581, per 23 Eliz. 1 ch. 9 {{harv|Raithby|1819a|p=671}}. The prohibition was strengthened in 1597, per 39 Eliz. 1 ch. 11 {{harv|Raithby|1819a|pp=911-912}}. It was loosened on 29 February 1620 {{harv|Green|1858|loc=vol. 112}}, and finally lifted sometime during 7 January 1662{{snd}}3 May 1662, per 14 Chas. 2 ch. 11 ({{harvnb|Raithby|1819b|pp=393-400}}, {{harvnb|Green|1861|loc=vol. 54 no. 12}}).</ref><ref group=note>9 Dec 1605 [Lon]. George Earl of Dunbar granted all duties on logwood, blockwood, &c. /CSPD Jas 1 vol 17 no xxx [December, 1605] / 1 Jul 1607 [Lon]. Commission to Ld Treasurer Salisbury, for new tax on every cwt. of logwood and other prohibited dyeing woods / 21 Sep 1607 [Lon]. Warrant for order to Officers of Ports, to demand duties on blockwood, logwood, and otherwoods imported for dyeing of cloths /CSPD Jas I vol 28 no xxx / 13 Jun 1608 Westminster. Warrant to pay Earl of Dunbar £4,000 in compensation of imposition laid upon logwood, Brazil wood, &c., which was formerly granted him in lieu of a patent for the sole manufacture of logwood, revoked by Parl /CSPD Jas 1 vol 34 no xxx / 1 Jul 1608 [Lon]. Commission to Earl of Salisbury to charge duty on logwood and other prohibited dyeing woods /CSPD Jas 1 vol 35 no xxx / 15 Jul 1608 Lon. Chamberlain to Carleton. Informs Earl of Dunbar has £2,000 in lieu of his patent for logwood. /CSPD Jas 1 vol 35 no 22 / 21 Oct 1608 Whitehall. Council to Sir Hen Lee [Lord Mayor and Recorder of Lon]. Require them to examine a project for fixing colours dyed with logwood, encloses petition for a grant of patent or monopoly of sole import and sale of logwood /CSPD Jas I vol 37 no 24 /CSPD Jas 1 addenda vol 39 no 62 /CSPD Jas 1 addenda vol xxx no xxx / 19 Jul 1615 Westminster. Grant to Rich. Giles of Lon office of seizing and burning all logwood and deceitful dyeing woods brought into Lon /CSPD Jas 1 vol 81 no xxx / 21 Nov 1615 Whitehall. Earl of Suffolk to Rich. Gyles, waiter for prohibited woods. To permit Marmaduke Peckett, merchant of Lon, transport a ton of Log consigned him by mistake /CSPD Jas 1 vol 83 no xxx / 22 Nov 1616 [Lon]. Grant to Rich. Gyles and John Wilson of office of Waiter, to search out and seize logwood, &c., for life /CSPD Jas 1 vol 89 no xxx / Jun 1618 [Lon]. Petition of Thos. Colbert, mariner, to Council, for restoration of logwood imported by him when ignorant of prohibition against logwood; promises to transport and sell it abroad /CSPD Jas 1 vol 97 no 139 / 29 Feb 1620 Whitehall. Proc prohibiting general import of logwood, but permitting Sir Thos. Compton to import 50 tons yearly, to be used in dyeing mean commodities only. All other logwood imported to be seized, half burnt, and other half delivered, for 6l. per ton, to Sir Thos. Compton. /CSPD Jas 1 vol 112 / 25 Jul 1620 Westminster. Commission to Ld Mayor of Lon, Master of Wards and others, to examine and discover abuses in importing of logwood, contrary to Proc and to Sir Thos. Compton's patent, and to punish offenders /CSPD Jas 1 vol 116 / 2 May 1621 [Lon]. Petition of Wardens, &c. of Dyer's Co. to House of Commons against licence granted to Sir Thos Compton to import 50 tons of logwood, the colour being deceitful, and much more imported on the pretext of these 50 tons /CSPD Jas 1 addenda vol 42 no 49 / 29 Aug 1621 Westminster. King to Council. To consider means for restraining importation of logwood, because proposals for its suppresion being brought before Parl, it is feared that during the interim of its sittings, large quantities may be brought in and secreted. It is to be seized, and all destroyed, except 6l. worth per ton, reserved for seizer /CSPD Jas 1 vol 122 no 96 / 20 Feb 1622 [Lon]. Dyer's Co found logwood in house of Daniel Tibergen and Peter Cozie, both aliens, but on Company’s trying to seize the logwood, the aliens’ wife and servants prevented it /CSPD Jas 1 vol 127 no 114 / 28 Apr 1622 [Lon]. King to Mayor, Recorder and Justices of Lon, &c. To seize some parcels of indigo, logwood, and other prohibited commodities now concealed in Lon, which he bestows upon Duke of Lenox, on condition of his exporting them /CSPD Jas 1 vol 129 no 67 / 28 May 1622 Inner Temple [Lon]. Sir Thos. Coventry and Sir Robt. Heath to Council. Send draft letter of assistance for patentee for suppressing logwood, ask whether legal and agreeable to precedent /CSPD Jas 1 vol 130 no 118 / 24 Jun 1622 [Lon]. Council to all Mayors, Justices, Admiralty and Custom House Officers. To assist Sir Thos. Compton in executing his patent for searching for and seizing logwood, which is forbidden to be used in dyeing /CSPD Jas 1 vol 131 no 65 / Mar 1625 [Lon]. Licence to Sir Thos Compton to import yearly 50 tons Log for 21 years, to be used in colouring haberdashers' wares, and not in dyeing cloth, reserving to HM 50l. per annum /CSPD Chas 1 vol 1 no 14 /CSPD Chas 1 vol 14 no 1–2 / 21 Jul 1628 [Lon]. Grant to Mary Countess of Buckingham of 108 tons Log, brought in among HM reprisal goods, in consideration whereof she surrenders letters patent heretofore made to Sir Thomas Compton, her late husband, of which term [21 yrs] 12 years are unexpired /CSPD Chas 1 vol 110 / 20 Apr 1635 [Lon]. Petition of Robt. Earl of Ancram to King. HM bestowed on petitioner the licence to import 50 tons logwood, whereupon petitioner contracted with William Wall, merchant of Lon, for importation of Log. Wall seeks to defeat petitioner of his contract, has raised himself a great estate by unlawful dealing in Log eg c 4 yrs ago Wall deceitfully imported 400 tons Log. Petitioner prays Wall be punished by Star Chamber /CSPD Chas 1 vol 287 no 11 /CSPD Chas 1 vol 380 no 70 /CSPD Chas 1 vol 391 no 124 / 12 Jan 1638 Whitehall. Order of Council on petition of John Tanner, merchant, who showed that c 18 months since the patentees for logwood contracted with him to bring in Log for his use, upon which petitioner got 12 tons fm Canary Islands to Lon, which is now seized upon pretence of some contentions between the Earl of Ancram and the patentees, who now leave the petitioner in this trouble. Desires leave to transport these, and additional 8 tons Log now arrived at Downs, into foreign parts. Ordered copies be delivered to Earl of Ancram and patentees /CSPD Chas 1 vol 378 no 62 /CSPD Chas 1 vol 379 no 15 / 4 May 1638 Inner Star Chamber [Lon]. Order of Council on petition of Martin Bradgate, merchant of Lon, praying he be allowed to transport 600 quintals of Log fm Canary Isl /CSPD Chas 1 vol 389 no 43–45 / 26 Mar 1639 [Lon]. Petition of Sir Richd. Titchborne to King. Five yrs since YM granted to Thomas Travers and Thomas Sara liberty to import yearly 50 tons of Log alias blockwood, with full power to seize all other Log imported contrary to law, for term of 21 yrs, paying Crown rent of 50l., which said patentees' names were only used in trust for petitioner and Sir Nicholas Fortescue, since deceased. That John Langston, porter of the Tower, contracted with petitioner to pay 400l. for his said grant, but now refuses to stand his bargain, for want of which petitioner is likely to be prejudiced 1,000l. Prays reference to Lord Privy Seal and Sec. Windebank. /CSPD Chas 1 vol 415 / 23 Nov 1640 [Lon]. List of patents under debate in Parl inc [Capt Crispe’s] patent for importation of 50 tons of logwood /CSPD Chas 1 vol 472 no 16 /CSPD Chas 1 vol 484 no 26 /v Socolow 478</ref>

'''1621'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1631: Great locust plague throughout [[Captaincy General of Yucatan|Spanish Yucatan]].{{sfn|Campos Goenaga|2012|p=145}}
* 3 June{{snd}}3 June: [[Dutch West India Company]] chartered.

'''1622'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': The [[Privy Council]] establish the [[Board of Trade]] 'for the consideration of all matters relating to Trade and Foreign Plantations.'
* 9 March{{snd}}27 January of 1624: Francisco de Mirones y Lezcano leads an {{lang|es|entrada}} towards the [[Peten Itza kingdom]], but some of the party are massacred at Sakalum at the instigation of Ah Kin Pol, a [[Maya religion|Mayan polytheistic]] priest.{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|loc=''lib.'' 10 ''cap.'' 2—3}}{{sfn|Cárdenas Valencia|1937|p=76}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=155, 187}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|pp=244-245}}{{sfn|Jones|1998|pp=48–49}}<ref group=note>In 1624 (27 January{{snd}}end of March), Fernando Camal and 150 Mayan residents of Oxkutzcab, under commission of Juan Bernardo Casanova and Antonio Méndez de Canzo, track down and kill Ah Kin Pol in retaliation for the Sakalum massacre (cf previous citations). / The massacres of 1623–1624 at Tah Itza and Sacalum are a major departure from previous Maya strategies of rebellion. Not since 1546 had execution as a tool of rebellion on such a large scale been seen in Yuc. {{harv|Jones|1989|p=187}}.</ref>

'''1623'''
* 1 January{{snd}}15 December: Franciscan fray Diego Delgado, with Fulano de Acosta, Cristóbal Na, 80 Mayan residents of Tipu, and 12 Spaniards, leads a {{lang|es|misión}} to [[Nojpetén|Nojpeten]], where they are detained and massacred.{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|loc=''lib.'' 10 ''cap.'' 2—3}}{{sfn|Cárdenas Valencia|1937|p=76}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=176}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|pp=244-245}}{{sfn|Awe|Helmke|2015|p=347}}{{sfn|Soza|1970b|pp=439–440}}<ref group=note>During the Delgado party's detention, Bernardino Ek led a rescue party of two Spaniards and several Mayans towards Nojpeten, and were likewise detained and killed (cf previous citations).</ref>

'''1625'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1630: [[Anglo-Spanish War (1625–1630)|Anglo-Spanish war]].
* 8 September{{snd}}8 September: [[Treaty of Southampton]] unites England and the [[Dutch Republic]] against the [[Spanish Empire]].{{citation needed|reason=not common knowledge|date=April 2022}}

'''1628'''
* 15 September{{snd}}20 December of 1630: Martín de Rojas, under commission of Íñigo de Argüelles Carvajal and the [[Real Audiencia of Mexico]], conducts {{lang|es|averiguación}} of the {{lang|es|municipio}} or district of Bacalar.{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=59}}{{sfn|Torres-Murciano|2018|loc=ninth para}}<ref group=note>Prompted by allegations against Juan de Vargas Asejas, [[Governor of Yucatán|governor of Spanish Yucatan]], accused of having caused retreat of significant numbers of Mayan residents to flee, via {{lang|es|repartimientos}} administered by {{lang|es|jueces de grana y agravios}} (cf previous citations).</ref>

'''1629'''
* 17 June{{snd}}7 September: [[Battle of St. Kitts (1629)|Battle of St. Christopher's]].<ref group=note>Many settlers escape to Mos Shore to cut logwood [brasiletto?] / See John A. Holm, PhD thesis for U of London, 1978, "The Creole English of Nicaragua's Moskito Coast", pp 179, 315 /v Latimer 81</ref>

=== 1630s ===

'''''sine data'''''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Residents of [[History of Honduras#Colonial Honduras|Spanish Honduras]] begin illicitly trading with Dutch and English ships at port.{{sfn|MacLeod|1973|pp=358-359, 462}}{{sfn|Zahedieh|1986|pp=216-217}}{{sfn|Obando Andrade|2016|pp=12-16}}{{sfn|García Paláez|1852|pp=122-126}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=24}}{{sfn|Pacheco|Cárdenas|Torres de Mendoza|1873|pp=239-304}}{{sfn|Fuensanta del Valle|Rayón|Zabálburu|1885|pp=197-198, 361-362}}{{sfn|Veitia Linaje|1672|pp=216-217|loc=''lib.'' 1}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': English, Dutch, or French pirates, privateers or buccaneers begin abducting Amerindian residents of [[Captaincy General of Yucatán|Spanish Yucatan]] and [[Captaincy General of Guatemala|Guatemala]] for sale at non-Spanish [[slave markets]].{{sfn|Bialuschewski|2017}}{{sfn|Bialuschewski|2020|p=239}}<ref group=note>This practice is thought to have lasted until {{circa|1665}} {{harv|Bialuschewski|2020|p=239}}.</ref>

'''1630'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Anthony Hilton of [[Saint Kitts|St. Christopher's]], with Christopher Wormely, Richard Bragg, Robert Wormely, Samuel Filby and about 150 Britons, settles [[Tortuga (Haiti)|Tortuga]].{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=103, 107-109}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=59}}{{sfn|Harlow|1924|p=x}}{{sfn|Bruce|1862|loc=vol. 198 item ''17 Jun 1631''}}{{sfn|Sainsbury|1860|loc=sec. ''May 1631'' item ''May 19. Warwick House.''}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or assault and burn Truxillo.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=108, 472, 825}}
* start of March{{snd}}end of March of 1631: Mayan residents of Xibun and Soite, {{lang|es|reducción}} towns on the [[Sibun River]], (illicitly) desert their settlements, whereupon Cristóbal Sánchez, {{lang|es|regidor}} and {{lang|es|alférez}} in Bacalar, with Mayan residents of Zacatan, (forcibly) resettles the deserters during a {{lang|es|reducción}}.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=199}}{{sfn|Gerhard|1979|p=72}}{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=60}}
* 4 December{{snd}}4 December: The [[Providence Island colony]] is chartered.{{sfn|Newton|1914|p=86}}

'''1631'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Providence Island's charter is expanded to encompass part of the district of Bacalar.{{sfn|Genkins|2018|p=69|loc=footnote no. 55}}
* start of April{{snd}}end of December: Martín Alfonso Tovilla, {{lang|es|alcalde ordinario}} of [[Cobán|Verapaz]], under commission of the [[Real Audiencia of Guatemala]], with Franciscan friar Francisco Morán, conducts a {{lang|es|reducción}} of [[Manche Chʼol]] deserters, but is threatened by the [[Peten Itza kingdom|Peten Itza]] military.{{sfn|Scholes|Adams|1960|loc=''lib.'' 1 ''cap.'' 24}}{{sfn|Jones|1998|p=49}}<ref group=note>Dated 1632 (''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'') by {{harvnb|Ximenes|1930|loc=''lib.'' 4 ''cap.'' 68}} and {{harvnb|Jones|1998|p=51}}.</ref>

'''1632'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or assault Truxillo.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|p=472}}

'''1633'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Anthony Hilton and Abraham Chamberlain pioneer the English dye-wood trade in Tortuga.{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=152, 289}}{{sfn|Kupperman|1993|pp=167, 310}}<ref group="note">Dated 1634 by {{harvnb|Newton|1914|p=212}}.</ref>
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Manche Ch'ol residents of some or various {{lang|es|reducción}} settlements in the Bacalar or Verapaz districts revolt.{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=18}}
* 26 April{{snd}}18 September: Jan Janszoon van Hoorn, under commission of the [[Dutch West India Company]], attempts to sack [[Trujillo, Honduras|Truxillo]], but upon finding the town abandoned, proceeds to raid [[Campeche City|Campeachy]].{{sfn|Goslinga|1971|p=226}}{{sfn|Baudot|1986|p=29|loc=footnote no. 15}}{{sfn|MY|1841|pp=142, 187–193, 235–240, 310–317}}{{sfn|Fernández Duro|1898|pp=115-116}}{{sfn|Laet|1934|pp=187-196}}{{sfn|Laet|1925|pp=407-413}}
* start of July{{snd}}end of March of 1634: [[Sussex Camock]], with [[Samuel Axe]], Nathaniel Goodman, [[Abraham Blauvelt]] and 50 men, under commission from Providence Island, establishes a trading post at [[Cabo Gracias a Dios|Cape Gracias a Dios]].{{sfn|Kupperman|1993|pp=95-98, 100-104}}{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=68-71}}{{sfn|Obando Andrade|2016|pp=11-12}}<ref group=note>Spring 1636 Trade Post abandoned {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=74}} / < Jun 1636 Cape Gracias a Dios. Two Du Capts fm Flushing land c 200 slaves among Mos Indians, possibly to be picked up later by Capt Willem Blauvelt aboard ship Expectation for Prov Co {{harv|Thornton|2017|pp=5–6}} / Slaves possibly fm Angola ship captured off Zamba Point near Cartagena {{harv|Thornton|2017|p=8}}.</ref>

'''1634'''
* 4 May{{snd}}end of July: [[Johannes van Walbeeck]] and [[Pierre le Grand (pirate)|Pierre le Grand]], under commission of the Dutch West India Company, establish a settlement at [[Curaçao]].
* start of December{{snd}}end of February of 1635: [[Ruy Fernández de Fuenmayor]], with 250 Spanish soldiers, captures the English settlement at Tortuga.{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=192-193}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|pp=60-61}}{{sfn|Harlow|1924|p=x}}{{sfn|Sainsbury|1860|loc=items nos. 200–201}}{{sfn|Fernández Duro|1899|p=35}}<ref group=note>A Spaniard, writing from S. Domingo in 1635, complains of an English buccaneer settlement at [Cape] Samana ... where they grew tobacco, and preyed on the ships sailing from Cartagena and S. Domingo for Spain {{Haring xxx fn 110</ref>

'''1635'''
* start of April{{snd}}end of June: Nicholas Reskeimer, with 80 English men aboard the ''Expectation'', re-settles Tortuga.{{sfn|Newton|1914|p=212}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|pp=61-62}}
* 2 July{{snd}}9 July: Nicolas de Judice, with 300 men aboard three ships, four shallops, one boat, leads a naval campaign against the Providence Island colony, but is shortly repulsed by [[Philip Bell (colonial administrator)|Phillip Bell]], [[Samuel Axe]], and the settlers.{{sfn|Newton|1914|p=196}}{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=79-83}}{{sfn|Sainsbury|1860|loc=items nos. 81, 83}}{{sfn|Bruce|1866|loc=vol. 307 item no. 19}}
* mid-August{{snd}}end of September of 1635: English, Dutch, or French pirates, privateers or buccaneers (130 men aboard an {{lang|es|urca}}) cruise near the district of Bacalar.{{sfn|Wright|1935|pp=*11–*12}}{{sfn|Goslinga|1971|p=235}}{{sfn|Laet|1937|p=190}}
* 27 December{{snd}}29 January in following year: Providence Island granted [[Letter of marque|letters of reprisal]] against the Spanish.{{sfn|Newton|1914|p=207}}{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=85-86}}{{sfn|Offen|2011|p=23}}{{sfn|Sainsbury|1860|loc=sec. ''January 1636'' item ''Janu. 29.''}}

'''1636'''
* 22 January{{snd}}22 January: [[Armada de Barlovento]] established.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|p=826}}{{sfn|Lang|1994|p=576}}{{sfn|Rojas Lima|2004|p=130}}<ref group="note">Dated 1598 by {{harvnb|Zahedieh|1990|p=166|loc=item no. 86}} and {{harvnb|Hussey|1929|pp=292-293, 296-297}}. On 1 November 1591, a ''real cédula'' instructs the [[Real Audiencia of Guatemala|President of Guatemala]] to raise taxes for an armada {{harv|Rubio Sánchez|1987|pp=131-132}}. Further see {{harvnb|Torres Ramírez|1981}} {{harv|Marley|2010a|p=34}}.</ref>
* start of March{{snd}}end of May: Providence Island commissions privateers [[William Rous]], John Leicester, Cornelius Billinger, Giles Mersh, and William Woodcock, instructing them to (among other things) impress Spanish pilots, including those familiar with the [[Bay of Honduras]].{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=224-226, 229, 230, 232, 234}}{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=87-88}}{{sfn|Offen|2011|p=32}}<ref group="note">Providence Island's first privateers (the ''Blessing'', the ''Expectation'', and the ''Hopewell'') were despatched in May 1636 {{harv|Newton|1914|p=226}}. Their last privateers (the ''Swallow'' and the ''Spy'') were despatched in July 1638 ({{harvnb|Newton|1914|p=266}}, {{harvnb|Sainsbury|1860|loc=sec. ''April 1638'' item ''April 20. Brooke House.''}}).</ref>
* mid-May{{snd}}end of May: Spanish Yucatan forbids the laying of logwood on open beaches.{{citation needed|reason=not common knowledge|date=April 2022}}
* start of June{{snd}}end of June: Providence Island is divested of Tortuga.{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=215-216}}

'''1637'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Tipu petition the [[Governor of Yucatan]] for relief from their resident {{lang|es|beneficiado y vicario}} and (non-resident) {{lang|es|vecinos}} of Bacalar.{{citation needed|reason=not common knowledge|date=April 2022}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Residents of [[Lamanai]] (illicitly) desert their settlement, but are shortly (forcibly) resettled during a {{lang|es|reducción}}.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=204}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Friar Gabriel de Zalazar attempts to resettle Manche Ch'ol deserters in the Bacalar or Verapaz districts during a {{lang|es|reducción}}, but fails to locate them.{{sfn|Ximenes|1930|loc=''lib.'' 4 ''cap.'' 69–70}}{{sfn|Jones|1998|p=51}}

'''1638'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Spanish capture of Tortuga.{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=62}}{{sfn|Charlevoix|Pers|1731|pp=9-10|loc=''lib.'' 7}}<ref group=note>An English adventurer [probably Capt. Fload /Haring xxx fn 98 /313–314 CSPC 1], some time after the Spanish descent of 1638 [on few Frenchmen settled at Tortuga], gathered a body of 300 of his compatriots in the island of Nevis near St. Kitts, and sailing for Tortuga dispossessed the few Frenchmen living there of the island. According to French accounts he was received amicably by the inhabitants and lived with them for four months, when he turned upon his hosts, disarmed them and marooned them upon the opposite shore of Hispaniola. /v Haring 63 /Charlevoix lib 7 pp 10-12 / See *Mémoire envoyé aux seigneurs de la CIA par M. de Poincy, 15 Nov 1640* [Saint Domingue et Paris, P. de Vaissière, 1909], Appendix I /v xxx /// By the end of 1639, ... [Tortuga] was occupied by some 300 inhabitants, mainly Eng, but with a large admixture of Frenchmen /Newton 280 [cites partially Egerton MS 2395 f 508 / Charlevoix lib 3 p 7]</ref>
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': [[1638 Tipu rebellion]], possibly aided by piratical raids and Peten Itza.{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=189-191, 204-210}}{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|loc=''lib.'' 11 ''cap.'' 12}}{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=50}}{{sfn|Cárdenas Valencia|1937|p=97}}<ref group="note">Onset of resistance to Bacalar dated 1630 by {{harvnb|Gerhard|1979|p=72}}.</ref><ref group=note>At mid-century the country south of Río Hondo was practically deserted {{harv|Gerhard|1979|p=72}}. /// Shortly before the Spanish withdrawal [fm Bacalar in 1650s], in 1639, there were still nineteen [Ma] village sites up to fifty leagues from Bacalar, although we are told that their inhabitants had recently fled to the Itzá country. /v Gerhard 73 /Egerton MS xxx / Shortly before the Spanish withdrawal, in 1639, there were still nineteen village sites up to fifty leagues from Bacalar, although we are told that their inhabitants had recently fled to the Itzá country {{harv|Gerhard|1979|p=73}}. / Of the 300 or so tributaries in the [Bacalar] province, something less than 200 were allied with those of Tipu {{harv|Jones|1989|p=206}}. / By 1642, after a blackout of reports [fm Bacalar, since 1638] on the situation, the governor [of Yuc] wrote that eight of the rebel towns, consisting of some 300 families, had been congregated at Tipu itself. Only six villages of some 150 families ... remained loyal to the [Sp] crown; but of these some had fled to the forests "either out of fear that they would be carried off by the rebels or for not being able to tolerate the weight of the work, being so few." {{harv|Jones|1989|p=210}}. / All of these events [eg massacres at Tah Itza in 1623, at Sacalum in 1624], ... were the prelude ot the dramatic collapse of Spanish control over most of the Maya towns of the Bacalar province beginning in 1638, the opening year of Katun 1 Ahau. This loss of colonial control was by 1642 replaced by a regenerated Maya leadership based at Tipu. {{harv|Jones|1989|p=190}} / Complicating our understanding of the period [1638–42] are the poorly understood effects of increasing depredations of foreign pirates along the eastern coasts [of Bacalar province], which ceertainly would have stimulated coastal Mayas to seek refuge in interior locations around Tipu. These depredations, in combination with independence movements at Tipu, had devastating implications for the villa of Bacalar, which was already in a weakened state due to its administration by an absentee leadership based at Valladolid. {{harv|Jones|1989|p=191}} / These [Sp, mulattos and mestizos of Bacalar], he [Gov of Yuc] said, numbered only about 50 and were a miserable, poor lot, living by going from village to vilage selling things which they bartered for the locally produced cacao. In so doing, he claimed, they extorted the Indians. {{harv|Jones|1989|p=205}} / [80 Ma from Manan and Chinam] have declared that by deceits and threats from the Indians of Tipu, by messages they had sent them that they were to give obedience to their king and wished them to abandon their town [Manan], saying that if they did not do so all would die and be finished, because at such a time the Itzas would come to kill them and there would be great mortalities and hurricanes that would flood the land. {{harv|Jones|1989|p=207}} /xxx [20 sep 1638] / Holpatin likewise received these reports from Tipu, per Bacalar intelligence {{harv|Jones|1989|p=208}} /// Para fines de 1638, únicamente permanecían leales a los españoles los mayas de la naboría de San Juan Extramuros [Bacalar], Pacha, Yumpetén, Coyte [Soite?], y Xibún. {{Barke B xxx /MEXICO,360,R.5,N.24 </ref>
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Friars [[Diego López de Cogolludo]] and Luis de Vivar cross the Bacalar district en route from [[Antigua Guatemala]] to Pacha (north of Bacalar).{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|loc=''lib.'' 9 ''cap.'' 5, ''lib.'' 12 ''cap.'' 16}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=160}}<ref group=note>1650 Fray de Cogolludo returns to Guat, possibly returning bia Hon /v Graham 160 /Cogolludo lib 12 cap 16</ref>
* 8 June{{snd}}8 June: Providence Island grant [[William Claiborne]] letters patent to settle [[Roatán|Roatan]].{{sfn|Kupperman|1993|pp=213, 280-281}}{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=267, 315}}{{sfn|Alsedo y Herrera|1883|p=123}}<ref group=note>The first settlement of the island by Englishmen did not last long, for they were expelled by the Spaniards in 1642 [and [some to most] either slaughtered or dispersed among the Indians {{harv|Newton|1914|p=315}}, but the connection of England with the Bay Islands subsisted through the eighteenth century and the claims to their possession were only abandoned some fifty years ago [1860s] {{harv|Newton|1914|p=267}} /// Engaged in “logwood” [unknown dyewood, or logwood dyed on mainland Yuc] cutting /AGCA xxx [Declaración... de Truxillo de M. A. Tamayo, 20 jun 1642] / Further see {{harvnb|Davidson|1974|p=15}} {{harv|McJunkin|1991|p=116}}.</ref>
* 13 September{{snd}}29 September: Mayan residents of {{lang|es|reducción}} towns in the district of Bacalar desert their settlements, whereupon the {{lang|es|cabildo}} and {{lang|es|vecinos}} of Bacalar (forcibly) resettle them during a {{lang|es|reducción}}.{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=207-208}}{{sfn|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=50}}

