=== 1630s ===

'''1638'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': A crew of shipwrecked [[buccaneers]] found [[Belize City|Belize]], the first English settlement or camp in the district of Bacalar.{{sfn|''anon.''|1829|p=40}}{{sfn|Avery|1900|p=333}}{{sfn|Bristowe|Wright|1888|p=23}}{{sfn|Swayne|1917|p=162}}<ref group="note">This date is traditionally given for the first English settlement in present-day Belize (further see {{harvnb|Finamore|1994|pp=21-24}}). A variety of alternative dates, however, have been proposed. These range from 1603 (by {{harvnb|Asturias|1925|pp=8-9}}) to 1717 (by {{harvnb|Carillo y Ancona|1878|pp=260-261}}).</ref><ref group=note>These buccaneers are further thought to have been lead by [[Peter Wallace (buccaneer)|Peter Wallace]] ({{harvnb|Craig|1969|p=55}}, {{harvnb|Curry, Jr.|1956|p=32}}, {{harvnb|Donohoe|1964|pp=27-28}}, {{harvnb|Gibbs|1883|pp=21-22}}, {{harvnb|Griffith|Alford|Bolland|2022|loc=third para}}, {{harvnb|Kinsbruner|Langer|2008|loc=first para}}, {{harvnb|Waight|2022|loc=second to fourth para}}). The details of this story are debated (see eg {{harvnb|Carillo y Ancona|1878|pp=260-261}}, {{harvnb|Asturias|1925|pp=8-9}}, {{harvnb|Finamore|1994|pp=21-24}}, {{harvnb|Ancona|1877|pp=5-8}}, {{harvnb|Ancona|1878|p=373-374}}, {{harvnb|Bulmer-Thomas|Bulmer-Thomas|2016}}, {{harvnb|Humphreys|1961|p=1}}).</ref>

=== 1640s ===

'''1640'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Dutch pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid Truxillo and Spanish or Amerindian settlements in the [[Amatique Bay]] and Truxillo.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=108, 472}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Morán misión Dominican fray Francisco Morán attempts to reduce runaway Manche Chol Mayas.{{sfn|Graham|2011|p=161}}
* 28 May{{snd}}30 May: Antonio Maldonado y Tejada, with 800 Spanish and 200 Afro-Caribbean men aboard a galleon and six frigates, leads a naval campaign against Providence, but is shortly repulsed.{{sfn|''anon.''|1642|pp=???}}{{sfn|Kupperman|1993|p=336|loc=footnote no. 49}}{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=295, 298}}{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=112-117}}
* 31 August{{snd}}31 August: A [[huguenot]] crew from [[Saint Kitts|St. Christopher's]], under commission of [[Phillippe de Longvilliers de Poincy]], capture Tortuga and expel its English settlers.{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=280-282}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=63}}{{sfn|Terte|1667a|loc=''cap.'' 6}}{{sfn|Charlevoix|Pers|1731|pp=7-11}}<ref group=note>[After French Capture in 1640] the English [were] expelled {{harv|Newton|1914|p=280}}, and sailed away to Prov ({{harvnb|Haring|1910|p=64}}, {{harvnb|Charlevoix|Pers|1731|loc=''lib.'' 7|pp=10-12}} / Charlevoix calls this man [Pres James] Willis ... Providence records repeatedly give the leader's name as Pres James. His real name may have been William James for Charlevoix's spelling of English names is very erratic, e.g. Waemaerd for Warner {{harv|Newton|1914|p=281|loc=footnote no. 10}}. / [T]henceforward Tortuga remained in French hands [despite Sp attacks in 1643, 1654] {{harv|Newton|1914|p=282}} = the coming of Levasseur the French had gradually elbowed them [Eng previously at Tortuga] out of the island, and compelled them either to retire to the Lesser Antilles or to prey upon their Spanish neighbours {{harv|Haring|1910|p=78}}.</ref>

'''1641'''
* 24 April{{snd}}end of August: Franciscan friar Bartolomé de Fuensalida leads a {{lang|es|misión}} to {{lang|es|reducción}} towns in the Bacalar district, but are compelled to retreat by threat of arms.{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|loc=''lib.'' 11 ''cap.'' 12—17}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=213}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|pp=248–249}}{{sfn|Chuchiak IV|2003|pp=241–246}}<ref group=note>misión headed by Fuensalida seeks to bring recently rebelled Ma in Bacalar province into submission to Sp, whereupon one party are denied passage via Tipuj, and are compelled to retreat at Zaczuz and Hubelna, while the other party off the coast of Hon meets with success [in Manche Chol towns = Soite, Cehake, Manan] (cf previous citations) / 1642 Frays Francisco de Fuensalida and Juan de Estrada reach Lamanai and upper Old R for a misión, reducción, or voyage ({{harvnb|Graham|2011|p=161}}, {{harvnb|Jones|1998|pp=214–224}}).</ref>
* 19 May{{snd}}25 May: [[Spanish capture of Providencia|Spanish capture of Providence]].{{sfn|''anon.''|1642|pp=???}}{{sfn|Winthrop|1826|p=34}}{{sfn|Kupperman|1993|p=336|loc=footnote no. 49}}{{sfn|Newton|1914|pp=295-303}}{{sfn|Genkins|2018|p=117}}<ref group=note>There were about 600 men capable of bearing arms [at Prov] {{harv|Newton|1914|p=299}}. / < Jun 1640 Eng sailor "Juan Simio" reports 500 men-at-arms in Prov {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=113}}. / 1641 Prov. 700 residents {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=113|loc=footnote no. 54}} / Further see {{harvnb|Games|1998|p=11}} /// A Spaniard, who had long acted as pilot to the Prov ships and had lately fled from them to Jam, ... [guided] Pimienta and the Conde de Castimellor [in landing their men at Prov on 24 May 1641] /Newton 301 /// Some of the English [at Prov] ... managed to make their escape in shallops to Henrietta and the Main, but almost all the principal colonists had been captured {{harv|Newton|1914|p=301}} / Captured residents sailed back to Sp; 400 captured slaves sold at auction in Porto Bello or Cartagena {{harv|Genkins|2018|p=120}} /// At Christopher's they [Mass. colonists, 30 men 5 women 8 children, in ships Salutation and Sparrow] heard that a great fleet of Sp ships was abroad, and that it was feared they had taken Providence, ... And coming to the Island, [Prov], they were shot at, Capt. William Peirce and Samuel Wakeman killed ... After this, the passengers being ashamed to return, would have been set on shore at Cape Grace de Dios, or Florida, or Virginia, but the seamen would not, ... they [seamen] came all home the 3rd of September following [1641] ({{harvnb|Newton|1914|p=304}}, {{harvnb|Winthrop|1826|p=34}}). /// Capt. Lane, Rev. Mr. Leverton [of Prov Co] cruised WI for some years after Final Capture {{harv|Newton|1914|p=305}}</ref>

'''1642'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] friar Francisco Morán (unsuccessfully) attempts to resettle [[Manche Ch'ol]] deserters to their {{lang|es|reducción}} towns in the Bacalar or Verapaz districts.{{sfn|Gage|1648|loc=''cap.'' 20}}{{sfn|Thompson|1938|p=592}}<ref group=note>1640 Fray Moran travels fm Vera Paz [Guat] to Bacalar in search of runaway Maya {{harv|Graham|2011|p=161}}. /// 5 Mar 1643 Bishop of Yuc informs Sp Crown SE Yuc reduced in 6 pueblos "hasta 130 familias" {{harv|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=50}}. /// Becerril—Tejero misión. Franciscan Frays Bartolomé Becerril, Martín Tejero pacify and reduce coastal [Manche Chol?] towns in southern Hon/v Graham 161 / Jones 224–226</ref>
* 22 August{{snd}}3 September of 1651: [[English Civil War]].
* 13 December{{snd}}13 December: [[Haulover Creek]] is called '{{lang|es|Río Balis}}' by {{lang|es|vecinos}} of Bacalar carrying mail to [[Antigua Guatemala]], this being the earliest (known) use of such phrase.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=324|loc=item no. 30}}

'''1644'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Construction begins on [[Castle of San Felipe de Lara]]./xxx<ref group=note>1604 Lake Izabal. 12-gun watchtower Sande Torréon destroyed in hostile assault / 1651–1652, 1687–1689,1736, 1797 Lake Izabal. Fort rebuilt, redesigned, or expanded /xxx</ref>
* 14 April{{snd}}28 June: Antonio Magaña de Solis, under commission of the Governor of Yucatan, conducts a {{lang|es|reducción}} of the district of Bacalar.{{sfn|López de Cogolludo|1688|loc=''lib.'' 12 ''cap.'' 1}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=228}}<ref group=note>5 Mar 1643 Bishop of Yuc informs Sp Crown SE Yuc reduced in 6 pueblos "hasta 130 familias" {{harv|Vazquez Barke|2012|p=50}}. /// Three parties of reduction = Salazar at Valladolid, Chancenote, Cozumel / León de Salazar at Campeachy / Magaña de Solis at Ichmul and Bacalar province /v Jones xxx /// Results = W Yuc, 2442 reduced / SE Yuc inc Bacalar province, 1900 reduced / NE Yuc 5081 reduced / Total = 9,423 reduced /v Jones 1</ref>

'''1648'''
