'''1654'''
* 10 January{{snd}}19 January: Gabriel Roxas de Valle-Figueroa, with 400 men aboard five vessels, leads campaign against the French settlement on Tortuga.{{sfn|Terte|1667a|loc=''cap.'' 6}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=82}}{{sfn|Marley|2010a|p=438}}
* 23 October{{snd}}end of May of 1656: Francisco Pérez leads five {{lang|es|reducciones}} in the Bacalar district, successfully resettling Chanlacan, Uatibil, Holpachay, and Holzuz, but failing to resettle Tipu and towns adjacent to it.{{sfn|Jones|1977|loc=''cap.'' 2}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=230—240}}{{sfn|Graham|2011|pp=249-???}}

'''1655'''
* 19 May{{snd}}27 May: [[Invasion of Jamaica]].
* 28 May{{snd}}''s.d.'': [[Oldman (king)|Oldman]] acquiesces to 'kindly use and relieve such straggling Englishmen as should chance to come [upon the [[Mosquito Coast|Mosquito Shore]]], with plantains, fish, and turtle.'{{sfn|Sloane|1707|pp=lxxvi–lxxvii}}{{sfn|Churchill|Churchill|1732|p=288}}<ref group=note> Though hospitality towards Englishmen observed < 1655, eg 1637 Arrival of a Bristol-man, call'd old Nicholas, fm St. Christophers, after having killed a man there, and put to sea in a small canoe, content to drive where the winds should guide him, and chanced to fall in with this [Mos] coast ... [where] he was kindly receiv'd by the Indians, and remain'd with them ever since /Churchill 6 288 / eg < 1641 visit to Charles I, possibly via aid or request of Prov Co., by Oldman, then Prince of Mos /Sloane 1 lxxvi–lxxvii / eg Acct of Mos Shore in 1765 by Lt Joseph Smith Speer. The first knowledge, & footing the English seem to have had of this part of the Coast, began in the time of the Buccaniers & Pirates in the Year 1630; at which time, and ever since these [Mos] Indians have maintained an inviolable Friendship and attachment to the English, despising all other People, and in all Wars with Spain, this has been the Asylum, and safe retreat for the Baymen. /ADM 7/837/(iii) f 2r / eg ≥ 1589 Mos. [Eng?] pirate camps established in Laguna de Perlas and Laguna de Bluefields, for smuggling with Mos /v Obando 11 citing Göetz von Houwalk, *Los alemanes en Nicaragua* [Managua, Fondo Cultura, 1975], 62, Link: https://www.enriquebolanos.org/libro/Los-Alemanes-en-Nicaragua-Göetz-Freiherr-von-Houwald though said information was NOT located in the cited reference /// Possibly see Prov Trade Expedition /Sloane 1 lxxvi–lxxvii</ref>
* start of December{{snd}}end of January of 1656: Elias Watts, with James Arundell and ten to twelve individuals, resettles Tortuga.{{sfn|Terte|1671a|p=126}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|pp=113-114}}

'''1658'''
* 5 April{{snd}}25 May: Spanish Yucatan is divested of the southern half of the district of Bacalar, which is transferred to Guatemala's district or {{lang|es|municipio}} of [[Cobán|Verapaz]].{{sfn|Marcus|1990|p=105}}{{sfn|García Paláez|1852|pp=94, 206}}

=== 1660s ===

'''1660'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Jérémie Deschamps, with Sieur de la Place, capture Tortuga.{{sfn|Terte|1671a|pp=135–138}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=116}}
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': [[François l'Olonnais]] sacks Truxillo.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|p=828}}/ Marley P xxx
* 8 May{{snd}}8 May: [[Stuart Restoration]].
* 16 May{{snd}}16 May: The [[Governor of Jamaica]] issues a let-pass to William James of the frigate ''America'' or ''American''.{{sfn|Marley|2010a|pp=189–190}}<ref group=note>21 Jan 1663 Port Royal. Capt James in America or American 6 guns 70 men sail with Commodore Myngs for Campeachy, though never reaches destination / Spring–Summer 1663 Capt Abraham Mitchell of ship Blessing reports "That about 90 leagues this side [E? W?] of Campeachy, he met three sail of the fleet, viz. Captain William James his ship, sunk in the sea by foul weather, who was the best ship in the fleet next the Admiral, and that many of their men in the fleet were dead" / Capt James = reputed discoverer of commercial value of logwood / Possibly see E. A. Cruikshank, *The Life of Sir Henry Morgan* [Toronto, Macmillan, 1935] / sn, *Interesting Tracts Relating to the Island of Jam* [St. Jago de la Vega, Lewis, Lunan & Jones, 1800] / Michael Pawson & David J. Buisseret, *Port Royal, Jamaica* [Oxford, Clarendon Press, 1975] /v Marley P 1 189–190</ref>
* 1 June{{snd}}1 June: The [[Secretary of State for the Southern Department]] is given responsibility over English colonies in the [[New World]] (this responsibility being shared with the [[Board of Trade]]).

'''1662'''
* 7 January{{snd}}3 May: The 1580{{snds}}1581 ban on logwood imports to England is lifted.{{sfn|Raithby|1819b|pp=393-400|loc=14 Chas 2 ch. 11}}{{sfn|Green|1861|loc=vol. 54 item no. 12}}
* 11 December{{snd}}11 December: [[Council of Jamaica]] resolve to attempt trade with [[Captaincy General of Guatemala|Spanish Guatemala]] (among others), by force of arms if necessary.{{sfn|Sainsbury|1880|loc=item no. 390}}{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=49}}<ref group=note>20 Sep 1662. Gov of Jam commissions Christopher Myngs, on frigate Griffith, to attack Sp shipping, towns, forts, so they "may be better inclyned to receive the settlement of a trade [ie accept Eng presence in WI]" / 5 Oct 1662. Assault of Santiago de Cuba / 1663. Assault of Campeachey [Yuc] / mis-identified as Campechuela [Cuba] by DNB / 21 Aug 1663. Arrival at Lon /DNB / Grainger 65–66</ref>

'''1663'''
* 9 January{{snd}}13 April: [[Sack of Campeche (1663)|Sack of Campeachy]].{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=107}}{{sfn|Knighton|2004|loc=sec. ''Spanish Main''}}<ref group=note>Christopher Myngs, Capt Thomas Morgan, Capt Edward Mansfield 12 t 14 Ships 1500 t 1600 men / Myngs and his fleet sailed away [fm Campeachy] on 23rd February, but the "Centurion" did not reach Port Royal until 13th April, and the rest of the fleet followed a few days later. /v Haring 108 /// According to the Spanish relation there were fourteen vessels in the English fleet, one large ship of forty-four guns (the "Centurion"?) and thirteen smaller ones. The discrepancy in the numbers of the fleet may be explained by the probability that other Jamn privateering vessels joined it after its departure from Port Royal. /Haring xxx fn 176 /// Possibly inc Henry Morgan /v Grainger 67 /// Purportedly to help [Bay of Campeachy] logwood-cutter who had been operating there for many years / See Dudley Pope, *Harry Morgan's Way: The Biography of Sir Henry Morgan, 1634–1684* [Lon, Secker & Warburg, 1977], 97 /v Latimer 138</ref>
* 28 April{{snd}} 28 April: [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] instructs the Governor of Jamaica to discourage privateering or buccaneering against the Spanish by soldiers or inhabitants, though he does not order the recall of existing commissions.{{sfn|Sainsbury|1880|loc=items nos. 441–443}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|p=110}}<ref group=note>[early 1664] Jam disallows public enlistment of men for trips against Sp /v Haring 110 /// 1 Jun 1664. Sir Thomas Modyford arrives at Jam, recently appointed Gov of Jam, under instructions to prohibit granting letters of marquee, and encourage friendly trade with Sp /v 635, 656, 664, 739, 744, 753, 762, 767, 786, 789, 811, 812 CSPC 5 / Haring 120 /// Friendly trade and suppression of buccaneers does not prove successful. “It is not in the power of the governor to have or suffer a commerce, nor will any necessity or advantage bring private Spaniards to Jam, for we and they have used too many mutual barbarisms to have a sudden correspondence. When the king was restored, the Spaniards thought the manners of the English nation changed too, and adventured twenty or thirty vessels to Jam for blacks, but the surprises and irruptions by C. Myngs, for whom the governor of San Domingo has upbraided the commissioners, made the Spaniards redouble their malice, and nothing but an order from Spain can give us admittance or trade.” /v Haring 121 /xxx CSPC 5 [T Lynch, 25 May xxx] /// Tortuga made suppression of buccaneering difficult /v Haring 122 /Add MS 11410 ff 16-25, 303 /786 CSPC 5 /// Though see 22 Feb 1666 Council of Jam "resolved that it is to the interest of the island to have letters of marque granted agains the Spaniard. 1. Because it furnishes the island with many necessary commodities at easy rates...with coin, bullion, cocoa, logwood, hides, tallow, indigo, cochineal, and many other commodities" /xxx CSPC 5 /v Botella-Ordinas 144 /// 26 Jun 1664 Port Royal. Sir Thomas Modyford proclaims "that for the future all acts of hostility against the Spaniards should cease" / Sep 1664 Port Royal. 2 Sp prizes of privateer Robert Searle restored by Gov Modyford to Santiago de Cuba, and Searle's ship impounded /v Marley P 1 442 /// 2 Feb 1665 Lon. Charles II authorises overseas grants of privateering commissions against Dutch /v Marley P 1 442 /// Nov 1665 Bluefields [Jam]. Gov Modyford meets 600 searovers, asks they stop victimising Sp as commissions are only against Du / Early Mar 1666 Jam. Gov Modyford authorises letters of marque against Sp /v Marley P 1 443</ref>

'''1665'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': [[Armada de Barlovento]] is reformed, on advice of the [[Casa de Contratación]], to better defend Spanish ports.{{sfn|Veitia Linaje|loc=''lib.'' 2 ''cap.'' 5 sec. no. 5}}{{sfn|Lang|1994|p=582}}
* 19 March{{snd}}29 June: [[Henry Morgan]], [[Jacob Fackman]], John Morris, David Martien, and ''Freeman'', with 200 pirates or buccaneers, circumnavigate the Yucatan peninsula, after having raided Campeachy, en route to raid Truxillo and [[Granada, Nicaragua|Granada]], likely raiding Spanish and Amerindian coastal settlements along the way.{{sfn|Marley|2010a|pp=137–139}}<ref group=note>Late 1664 Capt Fackman joins John Morris, David Martien, Henry Morgan, Capt Freeman in sm expedition against Sp in Gulf of Mex, possibly while cruising near Yuc [after Sacking of Campeachy in early 1663], and possibly as reprisal for Aug 1664 probes against Eng loggers in Laguna de Terminos by Mateo Alonso de Huidobro / Jan 1665 Jam. Capts Morries, Martien, Morgan, Fackman and Freeman with a few vessels and 200 men sail for Campeachy / 19 Feb–19 Mar 1665 Capts seize Sp frigate in Campeachy, possibly sack Santa María de la Frontera [hamlet on Grijalva R mouth], sack Villahermosa de Tabasco [50 miles up Grijalva R], while 3 Sp Frigs 270 men sent fm Campeachy by Lt-Gov Antonio Maldonado de Aldana seize their ships at River's mouth and crew them with 300 militiamen under Capt José Aldana, which force thereafter repels the buccaneers / Summer 1665 Buccaneers reach Roatan to water after having hugged Yuc coast [inc Hon?], and thereafter assault Truxillo, and continue to Cape Gracias a Dios and Mos Shore, where they hire Mos for surprise raid on Granada [Nicaragua] on 29 Jun 1665 / Possibly see Dudley Pope, *Henry Morgan's Way: The Biography of Sir Henry Morgan, 1635–1684* [Lon, Secker & Warburg, 1977] / sn, *Interesting Tracts Relating to the Island of Jamaica* [St. Jago de la Vega, Lewis, Lunan & Jones, 1800] / Juan Juárez Moreno, *Piratas y corsarios en Veracruz y Campeachy* [Seville, Escuela de Estudios Hispano-americanos, 1972] /v Marley P 1 137–139 /// Possibly see 1665 Sto Tomás de Castilla, Granada attacked by Pir / 1665 Granada attacked by John Davis /v Lujan 2 472, 828</ref>

'''1666'''
* 25 May{{snd}}26 May: [[Edward Mansvelt]], with 500 men aboard 15 vessels, recaptures Providence.{{sfn|Genkins|2018|pp=134-140}}{{sfn|Esquemeling|1914|pp=54, 102-112}}<ref group=note>See 1666 Prov map in AGI, MP-PANAMA,77 /v Genkins 136 /// 22 Feb 1666 Council of Jam "resolved that it is to the interest of the island to have letters of marque granted agains the Spaniard. 1. Because it furnishes the island with many necessary commodities at easy rates...with coin, bullion, cocoa, logwood, hides, tallow, indigo, cochineal, and many other commodities" /xxx CSPC 5 /v Botella-Ordinas 144 /// Summer 1667 Prov. Cartagena force retakes Prov; 3 slaves inform arriving force privateers present ≤ 100, w meagre defences; most privateers allowed to flee /v Genkins 139–140 /SANTA_FE,L.223 /// Dec 1670 Prov. Capt Henry Morgan captures Prov without battle, though with a staged skirmish, en route to Panama /v Genkins 141 /Exquemeling xxx /SANTA_FE,L.223 [Ramírez a SM a 13 oct 1671 / Salazar a 8 jul 1672] / Capt Morgan fleet for Panama = 36 Ships 1,846 men inc a French vessel, Saint-Jean [= 80 tonnes 10 guns 80 men], Capt Diego el Mulato /CO 138/1 f 105 /v Marley P 1 432 [doc no 8] /// 29 Jun 1665 Granada [Nicaragua, upstream of San Juan R] Morris and Martien sack Granada / 8 Apr 1666 Costa Rica. Mansfield [w sev hundred men, 7 Eng buccaneer ships, 5 lesser vessels, 2 prizes] leads unsuccessful invasion of Costa Rica /v Marley P 1 443 /// Mansfield force given as 2 Frigs 3 Sloops > 100 Eng + 80 Fr in Marley P 1 443 /// Possibly see 1666 Golfo Dulce. Fort of San Felipe de Lara attacked by pirates /v Zamora 178</ref>

'''1667'''
* 3 May{{snd}}3 May: [[Treaty of Madrid (1667)]].
* start of June{{snd}}end of June of 1668: [[François l'Olonnais]], with Mozes van Klijn and 700 men aboard a ship and five craft, sacks [[Puerto Cortés|Puerto Caballos]], attempts to sack [[San Pedro Sula]], and cruises the [[Amatique Bay]].{{sfn|Marley|1998|p=263}}{{sfn|Bialuschewski|2020|p=243}}{{sfn|Marley|2010a|pp=287–288, 389–390, 287–288}}<ref group=note>Sep–Nov 1667 L’Olonnais 6 Vessels 350 men retreat to cayes north of Amatique Bay / 4 Maya traders 1 PA impressed off Hon or Sp Hon /v Bialuschewski G 245 /GUATEMALA,39,R.43,N.199 /// Nov 1667–May 1668 L’Olonnais camps Abraham’s Caye, and trades with Maya fishermen there, and Maya traders from mainland, eg fm Tipuj, giving metal tools and raw iron for foodstuff / thereafter raid 2 Maya villages / Maya possibly engage raiders in one of these raids /v Bialuschewski G p 246 /GUATEMALA,22,R.1,N.11 /ANOM Marine 3JJ 282 no 10 /ESCRIBANIA,1092A, pieza 16 ff 9–17 /// Possibly see Spring 1666 Amatique Bay. Juan de la Cruz and 3 companions captured by 30 Fr buccaneers in 3 lg boats, then carried to Abraham's Caye [= Bluefields, Nicaragua] and impressed by Capt L'Olonnais /v Marley P 1 2 /// Possibly see 20 May 1668 Garate a Rey. Informa enemigo entro por Puerto Caballos, saqueo y quemo Sn Pedro [Sp Hon] /v Garcia P 2 95</ref>

=== 1670s ===

'''1670'''
* 18 July{{snd}}18 July: [[Treaty of Madrid (1670)|Treaty of Madrid]].<ref group=note>10 Mar 1671 Gov of Jam Thomas Lynch claims right to Sp Main settlements by uti possidetis under 1670 Treaty of Madrid /742 CSPC xxx [pp 322–323] / Barke H 146 / Hanna 118–19 / Socolow 480–481 // Similar claims made re Cayman Isl, Virgin Isl, St Lucia, Tobago, other islands /v Hanna 118 /CO 324/7 ff 152–159 /Add MS 11410 ff 266v–267 /Sloane lxxxvii /1066 CSPC 11 [7 May 1683 p 429] /// 10 May 1672 Godolphin to Arlington. Recommends HM not authorise logwood settlements, but rather connive at them / See Historical Manuscripts Commissison, *Weston Papers*, 10th report [Lon, sn, 1885], appendix, part 1 pp 200–201 /v Socolow 280 /// 16 May 1672 Modyford to Arlington. Recommends uti posseditis claim be made under American / Godolphin Treaty for Campeachy or Hon /v Socolow 180 /v Burdon 1 53 /// 22 Jun 1672 Queen Regent of Spain issues real cédula to treat invaders and those who trade without licence [inc Baymen] as pirates /38–45 CSPC 30 /v Botella-Ordinas 146 /// Re [contemporaneous?] Spanish complaints of Eng logging see Bib Esp MS 13979 ff 439–440 [Apuntes sobre el corte del palo de Campeachy, con un croquis de Guat] /v Botella-Ordinas 147</ref>

'''1671'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1677: Friar Geronimo Naranjo is well-received Manche Ch'ol residents of the Verapaz district, resulting in a series of {{lang|es|misiones}} and {{lang|es|reducciones}} in the district, principally by friars José Delgado and Francisco Gallegos.{{sfn|Thompson|1938|p=592}}{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=18}}<ref group=note>Includes Delgado misión of 1677 and Sp encounters with Bartholomew Sharp at St. George’s /// 1678 [S Hon?] Some or vars Chol Mayans burn their reducción settlements and flee /v Bolland F 18</ref>

'''1672'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or attack Truxillo and a nearby Spanish or Amerindian settlement.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=472, 829}}
* 22 June{{snd}}22 June: A {{lang|es|real cédula}} deems English logging in Spanish dominions ''piracy'', directing Spanish governors to treat English loggers as pirates.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|pp=53–54}}{{sfn|Anderson|2007|p=211}}<ref group=note>1669 Spain authorises Sp governors' issuance of commissions against Eng /v Zahedieh F 155 /CO 138/1 ff 43, 46, 136 [Modyford to Arlington 6 Jul 1670 / Considerations fm Modyford for fitting privateers]</ref>

'''1674'''
* start of March{{snd}}mid-March: The Board of Trade is instructed to furnish 'all papers belonging to this Councell concerning Cutting Logwood,' on account of the 22 June 1672 {{lang|es|real cédula}} deeming logging as piracy.{{sfn|Botella–Ordinas|2010|pp=142–143, 147}}<ref group=note>Logwood question considered in BOT < 1674 eg Jun–Nov 1670 Modyford to BOT in 120–122 CSPC 7 / 28 Sep 1670 in 108 CSPPC 7 / 18 Dec 1670 in 142 CSPC 7 / 25 Dec 1671 in 310 CSPC 7 / 10 May 1672 in 357–359 CSPC 7 / 3–5 Nov 1672 in 425–428 CSPC 7 / 1 Jan 1673 in 1016 CSPC 7 /v Botella-Ordinas 143–144, 161 no 6 /// See also 27 Feb–11 Mar 1674 in 556–559 CSPC 7 / 20 Nov 1674 in 622–624 CSPC 7 /v Botella-Ordinas 161 no 11</ref>

'''1676'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or assault Truxillo.{{sfn|Rodríguez del Valle|1960|p=33}}<ref group=note>1676 Truxillo. Fr corsaire seizes frig La Concordia /v Rodriguez C 33 /GUATEMALA,25</ref>

'''1677'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Dominican friar Joseph Delgado, en route from [[Antigua Guatemala]] to Merida, is denied passage via Tipu.{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=248-249}}{{sfn|García Paláez|1852|pp=121-129}}{{sfn|Thompson|1972|pp=??? [transcription of Delgado accounts]}}{{Thompson 22

'''1678'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Antonio de Ayora Porras leads an {{lang|es|entrada}} towards Chaclol and (possibly) Tipu.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=245}}<ref group=note>Chaclol = 90 [Sp] leagues beyond [S?] Hopelchen [possibly near Tipuj] /v Jones 247 /xxx /// 1678 Tipuj. 600 Mayas reportedly baptised /v Jones 245–248 /xxx</ref>
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or assault Truxillo and Verapaz.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=472, 829}}

'''1679'''
* 22 May{{snd}}22 May: Board of Trade deems English territorial claims to logwood districts (in Spanish lands) untenable, further instructing Jamaica to discourage such logging.{{sfn|Sainsbury|Fortescue|1896|pp=pp 364–366}}{{sfn|Marcus|1990|p=41}}{{sfn|Botella-Ordinas|2010|p=147}}{{sfn|Socolow|1996|pp=480–481}}<ref group=note>1677 Armada de Barlovento campaign against loggers in Laguna de Terminos /v Botella-Ordinas 147 /// See *Acts of the Privy Council of England, Colonial Series*, 6 vols [Hereford and Lon, sn, 1908–1912], vol 1 pp 814, 835 / xxx CSPC xxx [vol for years 1677–1680, nos or pp 343, 346, 364–365] / xxx CSPC xxx [vol for yrs 1681–1685, no or p 284] /v Socolow 481</ref>
* 26 September{{snd}}26 September: [[John Coxon (pirate)|John Coxon]] captures a Spanish merchantman laden with indigo.{{sfn|Sainsbury|Fortescue|1896|loc=items nos. 1498, 1150, 1188, 1199, 1516}}{{sfn|Marley|2010a|p=90}}{{sfn|Latimer|2009|p=236}}<ref group=note>Summer 1679 Capt Coxon sails towards Bay of Honduras [Hon?] / late Oct 1670 Jam. There has been lately taken from the Spaniards by Coxon, Bartholomew Sharpe, Bothing, and Hawkins [Richard Sawkins?] with their crew, 500 chests of indigo, a great quantity of cacao, cochineal, tortoise shell, money, and plate. Much is brought into this country already, and the rest expected. / Early Nov 1679 Jam. Lord Carlisle instructs HMS Hunter to arrest any rogue privateers attempting to land Sp indigo / Late Dec 1679 Port Morant [Jam]. Capts Cornelius Essex, Sharpe, Robert Allison, Thomas Magott agree to unite under Capt Coxon's leadership for assault on Portobello, citing outdated Fr and Eng commissions, inc let-passes fm Lord Carlisle to "go into the Bay of Honduras to cut logwood” /xxx /v Marley P 1 90, 127 /// See Gilbert M. Joseph, *Terrae Incognitae* 12(sn), "John Coxon and the Role of Buccaneering in the Settlement of the Yuc Colonial Frontier" [1980], 65–84 /v Latimer 308 no 49 /// Possibly see 1679 Bodegas del Golfo [Lake Izabal?] attacked by Pir /v Lujan 2 108 /// Possibly see 30 Jul 1679 Bodegas [Golfo Dulce] Alvarado de Villacreces Cueva y Guzmán a Pres de Guat. Informs Bodegas in Golfo Dulce sacked on 28 Jul 1679 by pirates in 7 canoes, who detained and kidnapped residents, and took 1 Balandra, 1 Barco luengo, 2 Lanchas, 800 t 1000 botijas de vino, 700 t 800 cajones de tinta, 16 t 20 petacas de pan and some olive oil /v Rodriguez C 33–35 /GUATEMALA,280 [Villacreces Cueva y Guzmán a Sierra a 30 jul 1679 / Testimoniado por Mantúfar a 1 ago 1679 / Alvarado a Pres a 2 ago 1679 / Arosemena a Pres a 4 ago 1679 / Pres al Rey a 6 abr 1680]</ref>

=== 1680s ===

'''1680'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Robert Oxe and 8 of his crew, aboard one vessel, are marooned at [[Turneffe Atoll|Turneffe]] by Pedro de Castro and Juan Corso aboard two {{lang|es|guardacostas}}.{{sfn|Marley|2010a|p=300}}/xxx CSPC 10 / xxx CSPC 11<ref group=note> > 16 May 1680 Capt Oxe sails away fm Bay of Campeachy in the Laurel, 35 tonnes, to "the Cays of Yuc for water" [Cozumel?], is then surprised by Sp GC, 2 of his men killed, Capt Oxe and remaining crew [≥ 8 men] put in canoe and thereafter land in Turneffe; are relieved 15 days later / Late 1680 Capt Oxe arrives at Port Royal /v Marley P 1 300</ref>

'''1683'''
* 17 May{{snd}}15 June: [[Attack on Veracruz]].{{sfn|Marley|2010a|pp=100–101, 158–159, 168–169, 381, 387–389}}{{sfn|Marley|2010b|p=824–825}}{{sfn|Latimer|2009|pp=246–249}}<ref group=note>1682 Hon [Sp Hon?] Fr Capt Blot and Capt Jan "Jantje" Willems sail to Honduras fm Cayman Islands in order to join 1683 Attack on Veracruz /v Marley P 1 49 /// Feb 1683 Petit-Goâve. Fr Gov grants letter of reprisal against Sp to Capt Nikolaas van Hoorn, who sails with Sieur de Grammont towards Central America [Hon?] to find Capt Graaf and Michiel Andrieszoon who were reputedly lying there with "two great ships, a bark, a sloop ... and 500 men" / xxx [Bay of Honduras] 2 large Sp merchantmen, Nuestra Señora de Consolación and Nuestra Señora de Regla, seized by Capt Graaf aboard his flagship Francesa; Capt Hoorn seizes 2 unladen [Sp] vessels, and disembarks [in Sp Hon] in search of indigo being brought to port / 7 Apr 1683 Roatan. Capt Graaf holds huge gathering of pirates, inc Capts Grammont and Hoorn, to propose assault against Veracruz; pirates agree, after which Capt Graaf sails northwards in Nuestra Señora de Regla and 1 other Sp prize [of Jan Willems], followed by fleet of 3 Ships 8 Sloops / 17 May–mid Jun 1683 Veracruz. Buccaneers take Veracruz, ransack it for 4 days, torture vars residents and move them to Isla de Sacrificios [where Graaf duels Hoorn], demand ransom for Veracruz fm Mexico City, which is received [= or in addition to 1,500 slaves], when Adm Diego Fernández de Zaldívar sights but does not pursue them / Late Jun 1683 Isla Mujeres. Buccaneers partition booty and go their separate ways /v Marley P 1 100–101 /// See David F. Marley, *Sack of Veracruz: The Great Pirate Raid of 1683* [Windsor, Ont. Netherlandic Press, 1993] /// Possibly see 1683 Bodegas del Golfo Dulce, and Verapaz via Río Polochic raided or attacked by Dutch pirate Juan Zanques /v Lujan 2 108</ref>
* start of December{{snd}}end of December: Juan Zanques, a Dutch pirate, privateer, or buccaneer, aboard three {{lang|es|periaguas}}, raids or attacks Bodegas del Golfo (on [[Lake Izabal]]) or the Castle of San Felipe de Lara.{{sfn|Rodríguez del Valle|1960|pp=40–41}}<ref group=note>Dec 1683. Du pirate Zanques enters Lake Izabal = Golfo Dulce, reaches Bodegas, enters R Polochic to Verapaz, reaches Turucub where they kidnap Indian Gaspar Quema and his wife, and retire /v Rodriguez C 40–41 /GUATEMALA,280</ref>

'''1684'''
* 27 April{{snd}}5 May: Juan Zanques, with 400 men (including Miskito mercenaries) aboard a {{lang|es|balandra}} and some {{lang|es|periaguas}}, (again) raids or attacks Bodegas del Golfo or the Castle of San Felipe de Lara, during which they engage 30 Spaniards.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=108, 472}}{{sfn|Rodríguez del Valle|1960|pp=41–43}}{{sfn|García Paláez|1852a|p=96}}
* start of September{{snd}}mid-October: Four {{lang|es|vecinos}} of Bacalar and three Franciscan friars (including Joseph Delgado) are massacred in Paliac by a party of ten to fourteen residents from Has, in retaliation for Joseph Delgado's having whipped a resident of standing.{{sfn|Jones|1989|pp=248–250, 328}}

'''1685'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Friar ''Cano'' (forcibly) resettles Manche Ch'ol residents of the Verapaz districts during one or several {{lang|es|reducciones}}.{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=18}}<ref group=note>1689 Some or vars recently reduced Manche Chol reducción settlements fall apart /v Bolland F 18 /// Possibly see [1686–1699 Guat] Confina este extendido territorio [de la Provincia del Golfo Dulce] por la parte de Medio-día de su asiento, y situación con el corregimiento de Cazabastlán; por el Sudoeste hasta el Poniente con la Provincia de Varapaz, y deste rumbo al Noroeste con gran región de indios infieles; y por la parte que mira al Septentrión con las riveras del Mar del Norte; mas por lo que mira al Leste confina con la gran Provincia de Honduras, sin que entre estos confines se le interponga otro alguno. /Fuentes 1 xiv–xx, 421 /Fuentes 2 290</ref>
* start of January{{snd}}end of September: [[Laurens de Graaf]] and [[Michel de Grammont]], with [[Jan Willems (Dutch buccaneer)|Jan Willems]], [[Michiel Andrieszoon]], [[Joseph Bannister]], Pierre Bot, and 700 buccaneers aboard ten ships, six sloops, and 17 {{lang|es|periaguas}}, raid Campeachy, during which they engage with {{HMS|Ruby|1652|6}} (David Mitchell captain) and Felipe de la Barrera y Villegas, Cristóbal Martínez de Acevedo, Juan Bruno de Téllez de Guzmán, and Andrés de Ochoa y Zárate.{{sfn|Fernández Duro|1899|pp=273–274}}{{sfn|Latimer|2009|pp=252–255}}{{sfn|Haring|1910|pp=245–246}}/ 193, 339, 378, 778 CSPC 8 / Marley P xxx<ref group=note>Jan 1685 Curaçao. Gov refuses buccaneers under de Graaf entry, after which they head to Hon [Sp Hon?] to plan attacks on Sp; is joined by more buccaneers inc Andrieszoon, Grammont, Willems, and up to 20 other Capts / Jun 1685 Hon or Sp Hon. Graaf and Grammont 6 Ships 6 Sloops 17 PA 4 sm Vessels 700 men towards Cape Catoche / 6 Jul–Sep 1685 Campeachy taken /v Latimer 252–255 /// Possibly see 1685 Castillo de San Felipe attacked by Pirate Juan Zanques /v Lujan 2 108 /// Possibly see 1685 Golfo Dulce. Vars parties of pirates enter R Dulce, R Montague /v Zamora 178 /// Possibly see 1685 Golfo Dulce. Juan Zanques and his men enter Golfo Dulce, Bodegas, Verapaz, reach Lunrub and kidnap an Indian /v Rodriguez C 47 /GUATEMALA,280 [Pres a Rey a 27 feb 1685] /// 1685 Guat. Pir enter Golfo Dulce in 21 PA, head to Verapaz /v Garcia P 2 121 /// 1684–1685 Old R. Nicholas van Horn, Dutch buccaneer, spends sm months logging at Hon, then leads or participates in 1685 Sack of Campeachy /v Joseph C 74–76 /1163 CSPC 11 [Jul 1683] /339 CSPC 12 [Aug 1685] /Blathwayt vol 25 [Molesworth to Blathwayt 4 May 1686]</ref>

'''1686'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or attack Verapaz and the Castle of San Felipe de Lara.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=108, 472, 830}}<ref group=note>See [1686–1699?] Amatique map in Fuentes 2 297 /// Possibly see [c 1686] San Felipe de Palma, ó Manaca [Castillo en Golfo Dulce ie Lake Izabal] ... por el año de 1686, que gobernaba el Gen Don Enrique Enríquez, dándole fuego el pyrata Yanquez, quedó desmantelado; hasta la entrada á la Presidencia del Gen Don Jacinto de Barrios Leal, que por el principio del año 1688, dió ordern á su reedificación; por la traza, y personal asistencia, del Ing y Sarg Mayor, Don Andrés de Urbina /Fuentes 2 294</ref>
* start of March{{snd}}end of March: Laurens de Graaf, with 500 buccaneers aboard seven ships, raids Spanish or Mayan settlements in [[Bay of Ascension]], and attempts to raid [[Valladolid, Yucatán|Valladolid]], but eventually retires to Roatan.{{sfn|Marley|2010b|p=847}}
* 17 August{{snd}}28 April of 1687: Juan del Castillo y Toledo is charged with retaliating for the Paliac massacre of 1684, but rather focusses on a {{lang|es|reducción}} just north of the [[Rio Hondo (Belize)|Hondo River]].{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=250}}

'''1687'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates, buccaneers or privateers raid or attack Bodegas del Golfo, Olancho and Santo Tomas de Castilla.{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005|pp=472, 830}}

'''1688'''
* start of February{{snd}}end of February: [[Jan Willems (Dutch buccaneer)|Jan Willems]] and [[Jacob Evertson]], with about 150 buccaneers about a ship, a bark, and a sloop, surprise a Spanish merchant ship in the Bay of Honduras.{{sfn|Marley|2010b|pp=588–589}}/xxx CSPC 12<ref group=note>Feb 1688 Albemarle reports "that the pirates Yankey [Willems] and Jacobs have fallen upon a great Sp ship in the Bay of Honduras called the Hulk [an urca], and that they had been in sight of her twelve hours. If Yankey failed in this attempt he is ruined, for it is said that he was very ill provided before." / Apr 1688 Albemarle confirms buccaneers fought and took the Sp ship "in the port of Cavana", but [shortly?] thereafter died / Late Summer 1688 NE. Capt Peterson appears with "the remainder of Yankey's and Jacob's company" /v Marley P 2 588–589 /// Possibly see 1688 Pres of Guat Jacinto Barrios Leal meets with Pirates in Puerto Caballos, but escapes / 1688 Bodegas del Golfo, Olancho raided or attacked by Pir /v Lujan 2 108, 472 /// Possibly see 17 Nov 1688 Bodegas [Golfo Dulce]. Incoming Pres of Guat Barrios Leal w 25 men fm Capt Juan Tomás Miluti meet Pir in 1 Frig 1 Barca, who make off w the President's 2 Barcas /v Rodriguez C 50 /v Garcia P 2 97–98 /// Possibly see 29 Sep 1688 Pres of Guat to Sp King. Informs Pir enter Valley of Truxillo by R Aguan, land 400 men, raid Truxillo, and attempt but fail to raid Olancho, abduct fm Truxillo a teniente de gobernador, 22 women, and others, and demand 5,000 pesos for their delivery /v Garcia P 2 121</ref>
* 27 September{{snd}}20 September of 1697: [[Nine Years' War]].

'''1689'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1695: Spanish military campaigns against Manche Ch'ol residents of the district of Verapaz.{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=18}}<ref group=note> ≥ 1689 Sp forcibly resettle Manche Chol to Guat highlands, where Chol are absorbed by Kekchi Mayans /v Bolland F 18</ref>
* 16 December{{snd}}16 December: [[Bill of Rights 1689]].

=== 1690s ===

'''1690'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Pirates or buccaneers raid or attack Spanish or Amerindian settlements in the Amatique Bay.{{sfn|Fuentes y Guzmán|1933|pp=296–297}}<ref group=note>[1691 Guat] [el pueblo de] *Amatique*, que llegara hasta treinta y cinco [vecinos] ... y por su número de vecinos al de ciento, y cuarenta habitadores ... en la contemplación de sus servicios [indios de Amatique = vigías] y buen celo, siendo asaltado por interpresa este pueblo de *Amatique* por el año pasado de 1690. Sin ejemplar á este tiempo en este pueblo, y hechos prisioneros los indios varones que en él halló el pirata, y conducidos á sus embarcaciones, pidió por su rescate una buena cantidad de maíces, que se le mandó dar muy promptamente por la libertad de los prisioneros, con cuyo aliento y experiencia perseveran más finos y leales en semejantes empleos [de vigía]. /Fuentes 2 296–297</ref>

'''1695'''
* start of April{{snd}}end of September: Francisco de Hariza y Arruyo, {{lang|es|alcalde ordinario}} in [[Bacalar]], leads a {{lang|es|visita}} to Tipu, from where he sends a (well-received) embassy to [[Nojpetén|Nojpeten]].{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=259}}{{sfn|Molina Solís|1913|p=350}}<ref group=note>1695—1696 Tipuj. 21 soldiers stationed there by Capt Hariza, fort built by soldiers [possibly = Str. H12-8] /v Graham 251–252 /v Jones 259–267 /xxx</ref>
* mid-August{{snd}}end of September: On Francico de Hariza y Arruyo’s urging or orders, Tipu send embassy to [[Mérida, Yucatán|Merida]] to render obedience, confirm local elections, and request priests.{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=259}}<ref group=note>Sep—Dec 1696 Tipuj. 9 secular priests sent to Tipu /v Graham 251–252 /v Jones 259–267 /xxx /// Possibly see relación by Franciscan Fray Andrés de Avendaño y Loyola in New Lib Ayer MS 1040 [Relazion de las dos entradas que hize a la conversion de los gentiles Ytzaex y Cehaches a 1696] inc map by Fray in Aliphat 863 / Laura Caso Barrera, *Dimensión Antropológica* 7(sn), "Discurso evangélico y conversión, Fray Andrés de Avendaño y la conquista del Itzá (1695–1697)" [1996] /v Aliphat 861</ref>
* 1 November{{snd}}26 December: A Tipuan embassy from [[Yalain]], pretending to represent Nojpeten, is sent to Merida, via and with help of Tipu and Francisco de Hariza y Arruyo, which is reciprocated by a {{lang|es|misión}} to Nojpeten, headed by Br. Gaspar de Güemes.{{sfn|MY|1842|pp=1–2, 5–10}}{{sfn|Villagutierre Soto-Mayor|loc=''lib.'' 8 ''cap.'' 4}}{{sfn|Jones|1989|p=262}}<ref group=note>The 4 residents of Yalain claimed to be Tah Itza representatives, but were later identified as Tipujans Ah Chan, Ah Chan Tan, Ah Tek, Ah Ku, at least 3 of which had previously been part of the Tipuj embassy to Merida, though they were close to residents of Yalain, whose priest-ruler, Chomax Zulu, was  "a great comrade and confidant of King Canek [of Tah Itza] ..." /v Jones 264 / It would thus appear that Ursúa and Hariza, once having seen the symbolic and political potential of Ah Chan's connections with both Tipu and Tah Itza, and having realized the possibility of establishing Yalain as a gateway tot he Itzas, decided to recognize Chan as an emissary of Can Ek and to establish Yalain as a legitimate Spanish Indian town. They must have sent Chan and his companions back to Tipu in September with instructions to return in December as a "full-dress" ambassadorial party. / See Avedaño, *Relation of Two Trips* [sl, sn, sd], 54 /v Jones 264</ref>

'''1697'''
* 13 March{{snd}}13 March: [[Spanish conquest of Petén#Conquest_of_the_central_lakes|Fall of Nojpeten]].{{sfn|Soza|1972b|pp=462–466, 479–480}}{{sfn|Villagutierre Soto-Mayor|1701|pp=588-605|loc=''lib.'' 9 ''cap.'' 9-10, ''lib.'' 10 ''cap.'' 1-2}}<ref group=note>1699 Nojpeten. Gen Urzúa [Yuc] formally transfers the recently conquered province of the Itzas [Peten] to Gen Melchor de Mencos [Guat], as ordered by Sp King Carlos II /v Soza xxx = ed 2 vol 2 p 481</ref>
* 20 September{{snd}}end of October: [[Peace of Ryswick]].

'''1698'''
* 2 November{{snd}}end of February of 1700: [[Darien scheme]].

'''1699'''
* 17 August{{snd}}17 August: [[Miskito people|Miskitu]] militiamen or mercenaries raid a Spanish settlement on the [[Patuca River]], (possibly) marking the first instance of Hispano-Miskitian hostilities.{{sfn|Sorsby|1969|p=11}}{{sfn|Thornton|2017|p=14}}<ref group=note>See 1699 Mos Shore map in Thornton 13 /// 2 Jun 1704 Alvarado reports Mos raid captured 8 men, 12 women, 20 boys / c 1710 Mos raid captures Chontal Indians /v Thornton 21 /GUATEMALA,299 ff 153v–54, 156 /GUATEMALA,300 f 84v /// c 1708–1709 Mos raids in Costa Rica /v Thornton 26 fn 60 / See León Fernández, *Colección de documentos para la historia de Costa Rica*, vol 9 [Barcelona, Viuda de Luis Tasso, 1907], 72–119 /// c 1709 or 1710 [?], Pres of Guat Toribio de Cosio, and Obispo of Nicaragua Francisco Benito Garret, informed re. Mos–Jam alliance, inc raids on Lemoa [near Golfo Dulce], San Antonio [Sp Hon?], and river towns on Río San Juan [near Verapaz] cf Bib Real DIG/II/2822 ff 312r–347r /v Barke H 174 fn 603 /// Though see, 1692 “The "zambos mosquitoes" penetrated the Caribbean coasts on three occasions "taking more than 200 people of their natives” in AFEHC Link: https://www.afehc-historia-centroamericana.org/index_action_crono/ /// Possibly see, 21 Jun 1740 Chiriqui Lagoon [Mos Shore] Hodgson to Trelawny. Reports sev Mos elders informed him that during King William and Queen Ann's wars [1688–1713] the King's Ships and Privateers came to Mos Shore to sponsor Mos raids [on Sp and Amerindians, for captives] in a more regular fashion [than at present] / See confirmation by Bishop Garret y Arloví in M. M. Peralta, *Costa Rica y Costa de Mosquitos: Documentos para la Historia de la jurisdicción territorial de Costa Rica y Colombia* [Paris, sn, 1898], 43–63 /v Offen M 51 /LC Vernon-Wager Force Collection 1740 series 8D/11 reel 92 /// 1702 San Pedro Sula [Sp Hon] attacked by zambos [Mos] / 1704 Fuerte [Castillo] de San Felipe attacked by zambos /v Lujan 3 683</ref>

