=== 1710s ===

'''1710'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1717: Great locust plague throughout Spanish Yucatan.{{sfn|Campos Goenaga|2012|p=145}}<ref group=note>1710–1736 Yuc. c 29,900 deaths /Hoggarth 91</ref>
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1720: Civil strife or war in the Mosquito Shore during the reigns of [[Jeremy II]] and [[Peter I of the Miskito nation|Peter I]] (and possibly Bernabe, a pretender or heir to the Mosquito Throne).{{sfn|Uring|1726|p=227}}{{sfn|Thornton|2017|pp=14–25}}<ref group=note>See sn, *Revista del Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica* 2(7–8), "Informe del Gobernador,” [1938], 366–384 /v xxx /// Nov 1711 Río Kruta [Mos]. Capt Nathaniel Uring reports indigenous Miskitu perceived Mulattoes [Zambos] as "new Upstarts" who "were got into the Govt and behaved with such pride and insolence" that the indigenous people broke with them and withdrew westward. /v Thornton 15 /Uring 227 /// xxx Matina. Zambos sink half of King Aníbel's fleet /v Thornton 17 / See *Revista del Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica* 2(7–8), "Informe del Gobernador” [1938], 366–84 /// 28 Aug 1718 R de los Plátanos. Sp emissary Joseph Bezero Lamartín meets with "so-called king of the Mosquitos" [Jeremy II?] and with "king of the Zambos" [Bernabé?] /v Thornton 17 /GUATEMALA,302 ff 635–636, 638v /// 1720 Gov of Costa Rica Diego de la Haya Fernández meets with Mos King Bernabé and Aníbel to form Sp–Mos alliance /v Thornton 18 / See *Revista del Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica* 2(7–8), “Informe del Gobernador” [1938], 366–384 / Possibly see repository mss re 1722 correspondence with Sp in Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Cartago 290 ff 2v, 31–31v, 37v–39 /v Thornton 19 fn 76 /// 8 Jun 1722 Declaración de Corella. Reports Jamn sloop threatened to take Bernabé, Pitar and Aníbel to Jam for wanting "to give obedience to the King of Spain, having already given it to the King of Lon" /v Thornton 24 / See repository mss in Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Cartago 290 f 38v /// 1727 Mos Shore smallpox epidemic kills half population, decimates 2 pueblos /v Thornton 21–22 / See repository mss Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Carago 325 f 241 /// 1728 Costa Rica. Vars witnesses disagree as to who King of Mos is; claims inc Aníbel replaced Bernabé as King, Pitar as King /v Thornton 20 / See repository mss in Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Cartago 325 ff 29, 52, 60 /// 3 Oct 1729 HM Mos to Hunter. Informs death of King Jeremy II, assumption of throne by King Peter I of Mos; reports "some disorders have happened lately among some of my subjects, inhabiting the outskirts of my Kingdom”; requests "Commissions sign'd with the Great Seal of the Island" for himself as King, Jn. Bellawy as Gov of Southern Mos Shore, Charles Holby as Gen of Northern Mos Shore /v Thornton 19 /514 CSPC 36 /// 15 Jan 1730 Bermúdez to Valderrama. Reports death of Gen Aníbel /v Thornton 20 / See respository mss in Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Cartago 325 f 128 /// 12 Feb 1730 Declaración de Juan y Francisco. Escaped slaves report Aníbel's son Beltrán replaced him, but that there was "great discord over who was to govern", and that a village near Mos Shore called Carte had risen up "and they [the Miskitu] had great wars among themselves over the said command [?]" /v Thornton 20 / See repository mss in Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Cartago 325 ff 131v–32 /// GUATEMALA 19 Apr 1730. Beltrán's occupation of the "throne" gave birth to a civil war, as "the inhabitants of the village of Carata refused obediene to the new king, followed by many ofthers of that barbarous nation [Mos Shore]" /v Thornton 20–21 /Gaceta de Guatemala xxx = 19 Apr 1730 /// 13 Nov 1731 Hunter to Board of Trade. Informs King Peter I of Mos still complaining of "his wars" /v Thornton 19 /CO 137/19 /// 20 Dec 1733 García Declaración. Declares King of Mos held African prisoners separate fm other prisoners, not allowing any mixture with Mos race; Mos Zambos were, according to King of Mos, the "worst people" /v Thornton 16 / See repository mss in Archivo Nacional de Costa Rica, Cartago 325 ff 2240v–41 /// Existence of civil war explicitly contradicted by Daniel Mendiola, *History Compass* 16(1), "The rise of the Mosquito Kingdom in Central America's Caribbean borderlands: Sources, questions, and enduring myths" [2016], 7 Link: https://hollis.harvard.edu/permalink/f/1mdq5o5/TN_cdi_proquest_journals_1983205346 /// Possibly see [Apr 1730 Guat] La [Gazeta de Guat] de abril [1730] dice. El dia 9 [abril?] convocó el M. ilustre señor presidente junta de guerra, y en ella se leyeron las cartas de los gobernadores de Nicaragua, Honduras y Costa-Rica, y los autos que siguió este en Cartago sobre las declaraciones de los indios del pueblo de Chiriquí, que estuvieron prisioneros en poder de los bárbaros mosquitos, y ahora lograron hacer fuga; los cuales declaran, que muerto el año pasado de [17]29 Anibel, que se llamaba rei de estos bárbaros, ocupó el trono su hijo Beltran, de que nació entre ellos una civil guerra, negando al nuevo rei la obediencia los avitadores del pueblo de Carate, seguidos de otros muchos de aquella bárbara nacion, que no conoce mas ley que su albedrío, ni tiene mas riqueza, que la que adquiere el robo, y algun comercio que tiene de los frutos, que lleva su pais con los ingleses, de quienes adquieren la pólvora y armas de fuego, con que infestan nuestras costas, y saquean nuestros pueblos, llevándose la gente: de la cual los hombres venden por esclavos á los ingleses, y las mugeres, que es su mas apreciable robo, aplican á su torpe uso, aziéndolas á todos comunes. ... y ahora declaran los fugitivos, que dirimida la civil discordia, y asegurado Beltran en el trono, aprestaba un gran armamento de piraguas y galeotas, cuyo destino ignoraban: /v Garcia P 2 163 /// [1729 Mos]. y dice la Gazeta de Mexico de Julio de 1730. que haviendo muerto el de 1729. Anibel, que se llamaba Rey de estos Barbaros [Mosquitos], ocupò el Trono su hijo Beltran, de que naciò entre ellos una guerra civil, pues los de Carare, y otros Pueblos le negaron la obediencia. /v Murillo 9 131–132</ref>

'''1711'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1735: [[South Sea Company]] establish trading post in Campeachy, where Spanish logwood is exchanged for [[Asiento de Negros|{{lang|es|asiento}} slaves]].{{sfn|Ledward|1930|pp=57-59|loc=vol. 44 sec. ''August, 1735''}}{{sfn|Socolow|1996|p=481|loc=footnote no. 13}}{{sfn|Sorsby|1975|pp=???}}<ref group=note>Possibly see 1736 SSC report re logwood in Elizabeth Donnan, *Documents Illustrative of the History of the Slave Trade to America*, 4 vols [Washington, sn, 1930–1935], vol 2 p 459 /v Socolow 490 /// 3 Jan 1719 Vera Cruz. Sp real orden to seize all SSC property reaches Vera Cruz, upon which 1,251 pesos of company property are seized at Campeachy /v Sorsby T 93–96 /// Apr 1735 Campeachy. Spain orders SSC to end slave sales at Campeachy, possibly in attempt to stem illegal cutting and export of logwood along Yuc fm Hon to Campeachy / Oct 1738 Campeachy. SSC leaves /U Mich Shelburne Papers vol 43 f 265 [Nasmyth to Burrell 14 Jul 1736] /INDIFERENTE,2792 [Geraldino a Patiño a 23 ago 1736] /INDIFERENTE,2851 [sn a Geraldino a 23 abr 1736 / Tyrry a Torrenueva a 26 feb 1736] /v Sorsby T 211 /// See partial SSC Campeachy shipping to 1739 in Sorsby T 258–423</ref>

'''1713'''
