'''1715'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Logwood is introduced to Jamaica, (likely) marking its first cultivation outside the [[Yucatan peninsula]].{{sfn|Sloane|1725|p=vii}}{{sfn|McJunkin|1991|p=238}}{{sfn|Finamore|1994|p=42}}{{sfn|Anderson|2007|pp=67–69}}{{sfn|GM|1752|p=141|loc=vol. 22 iss. ''s.n.'' dated ''s.d.'' March 1752}}<ref group=note>Logwood likely endemic to upper Yuc mainland, and absent in its offshore islands eg Cozumel /McJunkin 230, 236 [though check presence of other dyewoods in Hon, WI etc esp Tortuga, Roatan] /// 1737 t mid-1740s. There is indeed some Logwood growing in Jam and intime great Quantities will be produced in this Island, though I doubt whether it will be Sufficient for the Consumption of England. /Knight H 435 / By 1756 logwood was growing in many parts of the island [Jam], especially in low swampy grounds /v McJunkin 238 / See P. Browne, *Civil and Natural History of Jam* [Lon, sn, 1756], 221 / E. Burke & W. Burke, *An Account of xxx* [Lon, sn, 1757], 69 /Long 3 754 /// Logwood introduced to Bahamas c 1721, probably fm Belize /v McJunkin 239 / See M. Catesby, *Natural History of xxx* [Lon, sn, 1743], 66 /// Possible pre-1715 exotic cultivation of logwood in Antigua [early 1600s, though no documentary evidence of, and only noted widespread range in 1850] /v McJunkin 254 / See D. R. Harris, xxx, "The invasion of oceanic islands by alien plants,” [1962] p 74, D. R. Harris, xxx, “Plants, animals, and man in the Outer Leeward Islands,” [1965] p 82</ref>
* 1 July{{snd}}6 December: Spanish siege of [[Laguna de Terminos]] leads to famine amongst resident English loggers.{{sfn|BNL|1715|p=2|loc=iss. no. 596 dated 19 September 1715}}{{sfn|BNL|1715|p=2|loc=iss. no. 599 dated 10 October 1715}}{{sfn|BNL|1716|p=2|loc=iss. no. 621 dated 12 March 1716}}{{sfn|BNL|1716|p=2|loc=iss. no. 629 dated 7 May 1716}}{{sfn|BNL|1716|p=2|loc=iss. no. 636 dated 25 June 1716}}{{sfn|BNL|1716|p=???|loc=iss. no. ??? dated 2 September 1716}}{{sfn|BNL|1716|p=???|loc=iss. no. ??? dated 12 September 1716}}{{sfn|BNL|1716|p=???|loc=iss. no. ??? 19 Sep 1716}}{{sfn|SP|1716|p=2|loc=iss. no. 2}}<ref group=note>Rhode-Island, Sep 16 [1715]. [A]rrived here Capt John Pampillion Commander of the Ship Samuel from Campeachy bound to Holland, who iforms that htere is near Two Hundred Men gon from that Place a Pyrating, and the few that remain are at the point of Starving, Provisions being very scarce and extraordinary dear, and that several Negroes dyed there for want of Provisions, and that all Persons that can get away, carry what they have with them, and desert the Place, there was but one Ship in the Bay when he came away. Outward Bound Thomas Brooks & William Wanton jun. for Lon. /Boston News-Letter 596 /// New-York, October 3 [1715]. The Ship George Augustus, Capt Huntington, and the Ship Brunswick Capt Holder Commander, are at Sandy Hook from Campeachy, bound for the Downs, they only touch here for Provisions, and have been eight Weeks from the Bay, and say there are some Pyrates thereabouts, and report that 250 of the Bay-Men in Two Sloops and some Periagars were designed to Campeachy, to burn the Shipping there, and that the Bristol Gally call'd the Royal George of 18 Guns, being in the Bay would be in danger of Being taken by them. /Boston News-Letter 599 /// Rhode-Island, March 2 [1716]. Arrived here are ... Territ Lester from Campeachy and Providence, ... bound to New-York, ... informs that the Spaniards has fortifyed the Wrecks both by Sea and Land, by Sea they have Nine Vessels of Force, who oblig'd several Jam Vessels that came here to shear off, whom he left in Providence, one of which shared a Hundred pound a Man. /Boston News-Letter 621 /// Piscataqua, May 4 [1716]. Capt John Cou[ill] arrived here last night in a Snow from Campeachy, six weeks Passage, who informs that nine weeks ago the Spaniards from Tabiscus, had intirely cut off the Western Lagoons and Island of Treas, and captivated 150 Men Whites and Blacks, burnt all the Logwood, destroy'd the Craft, took a Pink and Sloop which they carryed away, burnt the Hulks and a Snow; they took Mr. Alexander Todd but he made his escape and is now in the Bay; They took also a Vessel of Marooners that belonged to they Bay and carryed to Campeachy Town, where they erected a mighty Gallows, and threaten to Hang them all. /Boston News-Letter 629 /// Rhode-Island, June 22 [1716]. Arrived here Chace from New-York, Benj. Tribes & Wm. Bree from Campeachy, the first bound to Dartmouth in South Britain, and the last for Boston, who informs that the Spaniards had taken several English Ships and Sloops, and cut off the most part of the Bay, and carried the Men away Prisoners. /Boston News-Letter 636 /// Boston, Aug. 6 [1716]. Capt. Wm. Bree, arrived some Days ag from the Bay of Campeachy, who Advises that the Spaniards had taken several Eng Ships and Sloops, cut off most part of the Bay and carried the Men away Prisoners. /Saturday’s Post 2 /// Possibly, see Boston News-Letter 534 2 = 12 Jul 1714 "Philadelphia, Jul 1. Capt William Goddard in a Ship of Boston is just now arriv'd from the Bay of Campeachy, who reports, that hte Spaniards are fitting out a Squadron of six men of War to cut off the Bay."</ref>
* 7 December{{snd}}10 December: Alonso Felipe de Andrade, with Juan de Astorga and 200 men aboard three frigates, leads a successful naval campaign against English loggers in Laguna de Terminos.{{sfn|MY|1841|pp=380–381}}{{sfn|Headlam|1930|loc=item no. 484 subitem no. x}}{{sfn|Molina Solís|1913|p=133}}{{sfn|Marley|2010b|pp=472, 487–488}}{{sfn|BNL|1717|p=2|loc=iss. no. 677 dated 8 April 1717}}{{sfn|BNL|1717|p=???|loc=iss. no. ??? dated 1 April 1717}}<ref group=note>New York, March 25h [1717]. Capt Nailor in 32 days from Jam touched at the Havana where he was informed that on the last Day of November five sail of Sp Vessels, went to the Bay of Campeachy (who having some days before stopt up all the Lagoons with Perryaugars and Armed Men, to prevent those that were cutting of Wood, from coming to the Shipping) And the first Ship they met was a large Dutch Flyboat, that lay at or near Triers; the Spanairds sent a Flagg of Truce aboard requiring her to Surrender, who finding themselves no able to resist surrender'd accordingly. ... Afterwards the Spaniards sent the Flagg of Truce among the English Shipping, which were one or two and Twenty, and finding they could not Muster above 80 Men together (the rest being in the Lagoons) The Spaniards being 600 Men, they also surrender'd Receiving the like civil Treatment the Duct had of Vessels to transport themselves. Between two and three hundred Men that were in the Lagoons have not surrender’d themselves, but are Raving about in Perryaugers. The Dutch Men went from the Bay to the Havana, from whence Capt. Nailor brought several of them hither. They say that most of the English Vessels taken in the Bay belong'd to Boston; and two or three were taken coming there, after the others had surrender'd; The Spaniards lying there with English Colours. /Boston News-Letter 677 /// Sargento mayor Alonso Felipe de Andrade /// [D]e órden de la corona de España, el virey de México dispuso en Veracruz una expedicion, cuyas fuerzas de desembarco se pusieron á las órdenes del sargento mayor D. Alonso Felipe de Andrade, que se unieron en Campeachy á las que en esta ciudad se organizaron con tal objeto. Reunidas las fuerzas se dirigieron á la Laguna, en donde alcanzaron una espléndida victoria el 16 de Julio de 1717, dia de la Vírgen del Cármen, de donde tomó su nombre la isla y la ciudad. /v Peniche 221 /// And possibly establishment of continuous settlement or retreat at St. George’s cf MEXICO,1017 [Cortaire a Rey, Mérida 4 may 1725] /v Calderon 104 fn 57 /// = Cause of Boston recession 1717–1718 /v Pitt 890–891 /// 7 Nov 1716 Monteleon to Methuen. Informs of Sp plan to dislodge loggers fm Campeachy on expiration of 8 months, requests George I forbid their trade to avoid this /201–202 CSPC xxx [Jan 1716–Jul 1717, 201–202] /v Socolow 485</ref>

