'''1736'''
* 7 September{{snd}}7 September: William Bunn, mate of the ''Tryal'', uses 100 counterfeit [[Spanish dollars]], whereupon merchants of Barcadares publish a print notice regarding the affair, (possibly) the first print notice published by Baymen.{{sfn|BEP|1736|p=2|loc=iss. no. 67 dated 22 November 1736}}<ref group=note>BOSTON. About a Wek ago Capt. Lothrop arrived here from the Bay of Hon, and brought with him the following Advertisement or Notification, ... TO all People whom it may Concern. We the Subscribers think our selves oblig'd in Duty to acquaint our Governments of a Parcel of Money, brought down by William Bunn, Mate of the Tryal Sloop, Thomas Pain Master, which said Money consists of Pieces of Eight and half Pistoles : The said Bunn passed One Hundred Pieces of Eigh on Board the Ship Hope of Holland, for sundry Goods, but this Day over hauling said Money, we found it to be counterfeit, which hope this will be of Means to prevent the passing of any such like Money in our Governments by said William Bunn, or any of his Accomplices. The Subscribers hereof have received each of them some of this Money to carry home as a Testimony, as Witness our Hands, Rivers Mouth of Beleeze, in the Bay of Honduras, Sept. 7th, 1736. Thomas Hill, Joseph Lothrop, John Hammer, Thomas Paine, Charles Davison, John Houlton, Alexander Stephenson. NB. The counterfeit Pieces which the Subscribers call Pieces of Eight seem to have been cast in Sand, and are in Imitation of Spanish Dollars, which are milled. A Sample of each of the Pieces mentioned in the above Advertisement may be seen at Col. Savage's in Draw Brige Street, in this Town. /Boston Evening-Post 67</ref>

