'''1768'''
* start of January{{snd}}11 August: Joseph Everett establishes a [[Packet trade|packet service]] to and from Belize or St. George's./xxx<ref group=note>Custom-House, New-York, Inward Entries [11 Aug 1768]. ... Honduras Packet, [Capt] Everet, [from] Honduras Bay. /New-York Journal 1336 3 = 11 Aug 1768 / NEW-YORK, Aug 15 [1768]. Monday last the Sloop Honduras Packet, Capt Everitt, arrived here in 38 Days from the Musqueto Shore: ... /New-York Gazette and Weekly Mercury 876 3 = 15 Aug 1768 /// CUSTOM-HOUSE, NEW-YORK, OUTWARDS [22 Aug 1768]. ... Sloop Honduras-Packet, Joseph Everett, for Jam. ... /New-York Gazette or Weekly Post-Boy 1338 3 = 22 Aug 1768 /// New-York, Jan 29 [1770]. Capt Craig, in 6 Weeks from the Bay of Hon, informs us, that Capt Armor, in the Honduras Packet, sailed fromt he Bay some Time before him, for this Port, but sprung a Leak a few Days after, was obliged to return, and the Vessel sunk soon after she got into the Bay, but it was expected she could be repaired again. /New-York Gazette and Weekly Mercury 953 3 = 29 Jan 1770</ref>
* start of June{{snd}}end of June: Magistrates (illicitly) arrest John Wright Stanly without trial.{{sfn|NYJ|1769|p=supp. 1|loc=iss. no. 1407 dated 21 December 1769}}<ref group=note>by Magistrates Jonathan Cowpland, Thomas Langon, William Wornick without trial / See account in New-York Journal 1407 Link: https://infoweb-newsbank-com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/apps/readex/doc?p=EANX&docref=image/v2%3A10DC31E31E090A88%40EANX-10DEECC34EFFA150%402367529-10DEECC3631A9280%400-10DEECC41B45EF00%40Philadelphia%252C%2B1st%2BDecember%252C%2B1769.%2Bto%2Bthe%2BImpartial%2BPublic</ref>
* 25 November{{snd}}26 November: William Harrop is murdered by his crew in Belize, whereupon the [[Grand Court]] remand them for trial at [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charlestown]]./xxx<ref group=note>PHILADELPHIA, Jan 12 [1769]. By Capt Albro, from the Bay of Hon (which he left the 26th of November) we learn, that the night before he sail'd, a difference arose between Capt Arpe, and his seamen, in a ship belonging to Liverpool, then lying at St. George's Key, when the Captain was stabbed in three different places, and expired soon afterwards; the murderers were all secured in iros, and were to be sent to Jam, in order to take their trials for the same: Capt Ivory, in a sloop for this port, was to sail a day or two after him.—He left in the Bay the Capts Anderson, Webb, Morris, Dowell, and Rogers, all belonging to New-York. /New-York Gazette or Weekly Post-Boy 1359 3 = 16 Jan 1769 /// CHARLES-TOWN, SC, Apr 17 [1769]. In the ship Bacchus, which arribed here on Friday, from Hon, was brought prisoner they unhappy person charged with the murder of Capt Hartop of the said ship, as formerly mentioned. This day the prisoner was committed to Gaol, and we hear will soon take his trial at a court of admiralty sessions. /New-York Gazette or Weekly Post-Boy 1374 2 = 1 May 1769 /// Charlestown, Apr 24 [1769]. To-morrow a Court of Admiralty Sessions is to be holden for the trial of one Turner, for the alledged murder of William Harropp, late Master of the ship Bacchus, on board the said ship when killed at the Bay of Hon. /Georgia Gazette 292 3 = 3 May 1769 /// LIVERPOOL, Mar 3 [1769]. By letters from the Bayof Hon, dated 12th of Dec. 1763, we are informed that on the 25th ult. at night, Capt William Harrop, of the Bacchus, hearing a noise among his men in the steerage, went to order them to their hammocks, which they all obeyed, except Matthew Turner, whom the Capt struck at for using abusive language. The man immediately seized the Capt's scimitar with one hand, and with the other gave him three stabs in the left breast with a long knife, of which wounds he expred instantly upon the quarter deck. By assistane from the ships in the harbour the murderer was secured. The next morning the coroner's jury brought in their verdict wilful murder, and the man himself has since contested the fact. As they have no authority to try for life there, the fellow is confined on board the ship to take his trial on her arrival. /Virginia Gazette 939 2 = 18 May 1769 / See verbatim in New-York Journal 1378 1 = 1 Jun 1769 [Supplement] Link: https://infoweb-newsbank-com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/apps/readex/doc?p=EANX&docref=image/v2%3A10DC31E31E090A88%40EANX-10DEEC83E5BA2460%402367326-10DEEC8400897B50%400-10DEEC84E634DA70%40Extract%2Bof%2Ba%2BLetter%2Bfrom%2Bthe%2BBay%2Bof%2BHonduras%252C%2BDated%2BDec.%2B12%252C%2B1768 /// See trial in New-York Gazette or Weekly Post-Boy 1377 2 = 22 May 1769 Link: https://infoweb-newsbank-com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/apps/readex/doc?p=EANX&docref=image/v2%3A10D34AE6B0969558%40EANX-10DAB09E4906EDA8%402367316-10DAB09E940778D0%401-10DAB09F5FDA4430%40Charles-Town%252C%2B%2528South-Carolina%2529%2BMay%2B2 /// Possibly see, NEW-YORK, Aug 30 [1773]. About two Months ago, died at Hon, of a Wound he received in a Scuffle with Mr. Hugh Mortry, of that Place, Mr. John Armstrong, formerly of this City: The Affair happened in the Night, and no Person being present, Mortry was sent to Jam to take his Trial. /New-York Gazette and Weekly Mercury 1140 3 = 30 Aug 1773</ref>

