* 8 May{{snd}}8 October: Juan Bautista Gual inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|p=337}}{{sfn|Bolland|1975|p=119}}<ref group=note>Despues del reconocimiento de Cayo-Cacina, tubo por conveniente Don Juan Bautista Gual, por denuncias que se le dieron, el partir a Cayo Bohel, y a Cayo Yngles, y en ambos encontrò habitaciones que hizo quemar, dando las demás porvidencias necesarias para el desalojo de los Individuos que contra lo estipulado entre las dos Coronas estaban alli establecidos, ... En los Rios referidos, a exêpcion del Hondo, halló porcion de plantios cultibados, y todos se destruyeron ... Sobre la Ribera Española del Walix a las sesenta y siete millas desu Boca, encontró tambien un rancho compuesto de Casas, Negros esclavos, Animales domesticos, y algun equipage; y haciendo quemas las Casas, decomisó lo demas con asistencia del comisario Ynglés, ... En la Boca del mismo Walix residia un Cuerpo de nueve Magistrados erigido por propia autoridad de los habitantes con grande repugnancia del Superintendente, y sin conocimiento de su Soberano, exerciendo jurisdiccion sobre todos los establecimientos baxo el regimen de juntarse de tiempo en tiempo para resolver los casos de justicia que occurrian, y tratar negocios de policia: y siendo todo sistema de Gobierno en aquel parage directamente contrario al Articulo 7,, de la convencion celegrada en 1786, requirió Don Juan Bautista Gual al Superintendente afin deque aboliese, y estinguiera el indicado Cuerpo: y anque este Gefe se vió en perplexidad segun le manifesto al referido Oficial para dar un paso tan grave como repugnante aun pueblo que no le tributava el mayor respeto; fueron por ultimo suficientes las eficaces y fundadas insinuaciones de Don Juan Bautista Gual para esforzarle à que diese noticia à los Ínfractores de su requerimiento, cuya diligencia produxo el efecto de la abolicion, y extincion pedida, ... y habiendola [la visita de los establecimientos Yngleses] extendido el expresado Ayudante mayor [Gual] hasta la Bahia de la Asencion con arreglo à las órdenes que le di ... solo notó la novedad de una Choza en la boca de la Bahia del Espiritu Santo, que por informes supo le habia servido à un Ynglés pescados llamado Juan Gregorio, hombre que algun dia puede causar graves perjuicios à esta Provincia, porque sobre ser un gran practico de su Costa, y de lo interior de ella, es sumamente desafecto a nuestra nacion: cuyo antecedente me hará aplicar oportunos medios de asegurar su persona, siempre que sea factible, baxo la calidad de infractor. ... Por lo respectivo à las ciento treinta y siete pieza de la propia madera [Caoba], que mi antecesor [Gov of Yuc] dejó al cuidado del Superintendente Don Eduardo Marcos Despard, contextó èste que las habian robado, y que despues de mucha diligencias no habia podido descubrir los delinqüentes. ... /SGU,LEG,6948,27 ff 233–xxx /// 30 May 1789 Sp King authorises subsistence plantations in Hon /CO 123/7 [Floridablanca to Merry 30 May 1789] / [≤ 1806] Every Settlement at Hon has its plantain walk; and many of these comprehend an extent of, at least, an hundred acres ... the pine-apple and melon, being very commonly interspersed between the rows of plantains ... [banks of the Sibun R are] thickly studded with plantations. /v Bolland F 59 /Henderson 42 /// 1789–1796 Belize T. [Re Sp Commissaries] until the commencement of the War [1796] the Sp visiting officers were extremely rigid in confining the Settlers to the precise quantity of ground allotted [= 500 yards for Prov], and destroyed such part of every Plantation that exceeded the same, where it came within their observations /CO 123/29 [Report 1820] /CO 123/18 [Trade Remarks] /v Bolland L 23</ref>
* 10 June{{snd}}10 June: The Public Meeting restrict suffrage by raising the property qualification to vote to 65 Jamaican pounds.{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=37}}
* 10 June{{snd}}10 June: Edward Despard dissolves the Bench of Magistrates and the courts, and proposes a new constitution of government, styled ''Plan of Police'', for the settlement.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=172}}{{sfn|Anderson|2007|p=277}}<ref group=note>itself made null and void 25 Nov 1789 /// 1789, June 10th. Plan of Police, by E. M. Despard. Police to consist of the Superintendent together with a Committee of 15 elected annually by the inhabitants, Superintendent to have power to summon or dismiss the Committee, but must call it every six months or oftener if required by a majority of the inhabitants. He may negative all its proceedings, he is to execute any Regulations made by it, to appoint all officials and judges and to remove the latter on the application of the Committee. He may remit penalties in the Courts. He is to have control of all expenditure. In event of war he will be Commander in Chief. The inhabitants if willing to accept are to subscribe to the Plan and promise obedience and assistance. On the arrival of any system of regulation from Great Britain it [this Plan] will become null and void. /v Burdon 1 /CO 123/8 /// Despard Plan of Police approved by 130 inhabitants; and condemned by 24 principal settlers, on 15 Jun 1789 /v Burdon 1 173 /CO 123/8 /// 1789. Petition by Settlers against Despard's Constitution. Contending that it was nto right for a small body, the Superintendent and fifteen other to have power to repeal or abrogate laws and regulations sanctioned by the whole Community: that all appropriations of money should remain to the people and not the Superintendent. "Englishmen can never brook the despotic government of an individual. We have tasted the sweets of liberty and hitherto have never forfeited our right and title to that valuable blessing ... " /v Burdon 1 174 /CO 123/8 /// 1789, November 25h. Advertisement. HM Superintendent ... publickly declares that he considers the present [Despard's] System of Police and all offices held under that Police to be from this Moment and henceforth forever annulled extinct and void. King's House, 25th November 1789. E. M. Despard. 4 O'Clock in the afternoon. /v Burdon 1 181 /CO 123/12</ref>
* 10 November{{snd}}10 November: Edward Despard is suspended (and later permanently relieved) from office, whereupon Peter Hunter is appointed Superintendent ({{lang|la|ad interim}} at first, {{lang|la|simpliciter}} later on).{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=178}}{{sfn|Anderson|2007|pp=281-282}}<ref group=note>later confirmed permanent on 4 Oct 1791 /// 1789, October 16th. Sec of State Grenville to Col. Hunter. Directs that on his arrival in the Bay he is to act as Superintendent until the restoration of Despard. He is to be under the direction of Lord Effingham but to write home too. He is to declare Despard's Plan of Police null and void and to consider the old system standing where it did in May last. He is to "learn the sentiments of the settlers" but "to keep in view the essential object of providing by such regulations for the due observance of the Convention [of Lon, 1786] by restraining HM Subjects within the Limits assigned to Them and by preventing them from engaging in any branch of commerce or Manufacture excepting only the Trade in Woods." /v Burdon 1 179 /CO 123/8 /// 1789, November 10th. Sec of State Grenville to Despard. Suspending him ... it is difficult to explain "the irregularity of the whole of those [Sp Commissary visits] proceedings" with the Spanish Commissary. The sole purpose of the visits by Spanish Officers is to see that no forts are erected by the Settlers, and the British commissaries accompany them to see that this purpose is fulfilled. The giving HM sanction and authority to the destruction of the Plantations by the Spanish Commissary was "an act highly exceptionable." Gual should have reported finding them to his superiors, as their status was doubtful and Spain has since given her consent to such cultivation. Similarly Gual should have been permitted to report the finding of the system of Magistrates to his superiors. Despard knew that the introduciton of a Plan of Police was under consideration in England. Even if Gual had been right in making the complaint and Despard had been authorised to abolish the Courts it would have been wrong to do so since the Settlement could not subsist without them and he himself proceeded to set up an alternative system "equally liable to the objection by which you declared the former to be illegal." /v Burdon 1 180 /CO 123/8 /// 1791, October 4th. Sec Dundas, Whitehall, to Col Despard. ... You were informed by Lord Grenville at the time of your suspension of the impression which HM Servants had received of your conduct from the Papers then before them. That impression not being done away ... I have only now to inform you that HM does not conceive it will be for the advantage of His Service to reinstate you ... /v Burdon 1 195 /CO 123/13 /// 18 May 1790 Col Hunter proposes Plan of Police /CO 123/9 [18 May 1790] /v Bolland F 40</ref>

=== 1790s ===

'''1790'''
* 8 January{{snd}}end of June: Rafael Llovet inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|p=339}}
* 12 April{{snd}}12 April: Peter Hunter restores Burnaby’s Code.{{sfn|''anon.''|1828|pp=???}}{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=184}}
* 23 April{{snd}}23 April: Public Meeting restrict suffrage, explicitly barring free people of colour from voting for Magistrates and members of the Public Meeting.{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=37}}<ref group=note>23 Apr 1790 Belize T. [Resolved that] any person entitled to vote at elections for Magistrates for this Settlement ... must be possessed of a fixed Habitation or a Negro Slave or a Mahogany or Logwood work or visible property to the amount of Eighty Pounds Current money of Jam and that no person of colour was allowed to vote /CO 123/12 [Minutes 23 Apr 1790] /v Bolland F 37 /// 3 May 1790 Belize T. Mags elections held, Col Despard elected with unprecedented [in records] 203 of 250 votes /v Bolland F 38 /CO 123/9 /// [1790 Belize T.] Four defeated Mags complain about Despard's canvassing techniques, number of ineligible votes, and breadth of the franchise, complain about "ignorant turtlers ... men of colour, possessing no species of property or an fixed residence" voting for Despard, saying "There are not above 76 wood cutters of all descriptions in the Bay of Honduras, of whom, at least, Twenty hardly deserve that name, and about 40 White housekeepers, being traders and tradesmen, so that, in our opinion, there cannot be above 110 good voters in the Settlement; and on this principle ... few of Colonel Despard's friends, or even himself, would have been returned as Magistrates" /v Bolland F 38 /CO 123/13 [Acct by Bartlet et al] /// Possibly see 13 Aug 1793 Belize T. Fourteen Mos evacuees or families petition to be permitted to return to the Mos Shore, stating they were unable to support themselves by cutting wood or growing provisions and did not wish to be "half British Subjects as we are at present" /v Bolland F 40 /CO 137/92 [Petition to Pitt 13 Aug 1793]</ref>
* start of September{{snd}}end of December: Baltasar Rodríguez de Truxillo inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary, but is unable to finish, whereupon Rafael Llovet attempts to finish the inspection.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|pp=342, 371}}<ref group=note>See 1790 Belize T. Translater to Sp commissioner, Peter Gonzalez, is arrested for "walking in the Negro section without good reason" and talking to slaves after dark; Mattias Gale accuses Gonzalez of attempting to recruit slaves James and Cudjoe; Cudjoe informs O'Brien that Gonzalez claimed to have recruited 100 slaves to scout Eng forts and troops, then set fire to Belize T, which would signal Sp vessels luking nearby to "come on boldly" /CO 123/13 f 173 [22 Nov 1790 / 24 Nov 1790] /CO 123/3 ff 175, 180 [Deposition of Gale 16 Dec 1790 / Deposition of Cudjoe 30 Nov 1790] /v Anderson M 343–344</ref>
* 22 October{{snd}}22 October: First census of the English settlement is published.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|p=364|loc=item no. 13}}{{sfn|Finamore|1994|p=93}}{{sfn|Bolland|1975|p=87}}<ref group=note>See 1787 Lamb Survey in CO 700 /v Finamore 90 / and 1790 “Present State of British Settlers in Honduras” in CO 123/9 f 248 /v Finamore 93 / and Sp Commissary inspections eg xxx /// Jan–Feb 1790 List of the Inhabitants of Honduras, taken by HM Sup, in Jan and Feb 1790, in consequence of HCM Consession of 30 May 1789, permitting them to cultivate gardens /CO 123/11 / 22 Oct 1790 General Return of the Inhabitants in the Bay of Honduras, Free people of every description and Slaves /CO 123/9 /// RAFAEL LLOBET A E. M. DESPARD, EN PIRAGUE DE LA ENCARCACION A LA BOCA DEL RIO WALIX, EN 26-1-1790. "... me es absolutamente necesario suplicar a V. S. se sirva tener la bondad de facilitarme una Relación firmada por V. S del nombre de los pretendients [para terrenos para huertas, conforme a las órdenes e instrucciones que al efecto ha impuesto el Sr. Gobernador y Capitán General de la Provincia de Yucatán], número de sus familias, y dependientes para que con conocimiento de las obligaciones de cada uno, determine yo lo conveniente. /v Calderon 364 /MEXICO,3023 [Gálvez a Alange a Mérida a 8 sep 1790] /// Though see 1786–1787 Census of Mos Shore evacuees [= 2,214 Shoremen, c 1,200 Baymen] /xxx /// Jan–Feb 1790 Belize T. List of Inhabitants re HCM Concession of 30 May 1789 = 2,915 total [738 free, 2,177 slaves], "besides fifty or sixty more (mostly persons employed in fishing and piloting) who did not give in their names for garden grounds", where 58 pc resident in "River Belize, its branches and creeks", 8 pc in "River Sibun and its branches", 34 pc in "Salt Creek, Northern River, Rowley's Bight and New River" /v Bolland F 41–42 /CO 123/11</ref>

'''1791'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Peter Hunter vacates the office of Superintendent, leaving the English settlement's government solely to the Bench of Magistrates and Public Meeting.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=193}}<ref group=note>Lon Jun 18 [1791]. Advices are received fm Hon, by way of Bristol, which mention the arrival of several ships fm America, with provisions, which had been much wanted for some time; and that the disturbances which had lately prevailed amongst the inhabitants, had been finally and amicably settled; and that everything remained quie; that several ships were then lading for England, and were appointed to sail the latter end of May. /Mail or Claypoole's Daily Advertiser [PA] 72 2 = 23 Aug 1791</ref>
* 21 August{{snd}}1 January of 1804: [[Haitian Revolution]].<ref group=note>26 Nov 1791 Belize T. Fr ships carrying > 200 St Domingue revolutionaries arrive, but Pub Mtg decide "they should not be permitted to land so infectious a cargo" /v Bolland F 75 /CO 123/13 [Bartlet to Dyer, Allan & Co 26 Nov 1791] /// 1800 Belize T. Pub Mtg discuss "apprehension of internal convulsion and the horrors of St. Domingo" /v Bolland F 75 /v Burdon 1 282 /// 5 Apr 1807 Belize T. Louis Sovereign, Fr Black man, "was for some time confined in Gaol here, and not long since transported fm hence, as a suspicious character ... [he] committed no crime here, but was sent fm the settlement, merely on account of his being originally fm St. Domingo" /CO 123/17 [Hamilton to Mags 5 Apr 1807] /// 29 May 1809 Belize T. Concern expressed re "the evil disposition of the Non Commissioned Officers belonging to the 5th West India Regiment, among whom are several who commanded Companies of black Troops in St. Domingo" /CO 123/18 [Dyer to Cooke 29 May 1809] /v Bolland F 75–76</ref>
* 1 September{{snd}}8 October: Rafael Llovet inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary, but is unable to do so on account of Peter Hunter’s departure without having named a English commissary.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|pp=348, 389}}<ref group=note>Galvez a Alange en Merida a 8 octubre 1791. ... Tal morosidad de parte del referido Governador [of Jam?] en responderme y proveer de Superintendente los establecimientos [Hon], me sugieren la vehemente presunción que sus designios se dirigen, cuando menos, a impedir se haga por el Comisario Español la visita prevenida en la Convención de 1786, logrando por consecuencia los colonos ingleses multiplicar sus infracciones tanto más, cuanto tarde el Comisario español, y como para impedir su ingreso estén prevenidos con la excusa de no haber sujeto autorizado por la Corte de Londres para nombrar al Comisario inglés que debe accompañar al español, resulta pues que con un pretexto, notoriamente frívolo, de que es causante el Gobierno británico, ... /v Calderon 389 /MEXICO,3024</ref>
* 11 October{{snd}}11 October: The Public Meeting criminalise [[obeah]], imposing the death sentence on practitioners, possibly marking the first {{lang|es|de jure}} restriction of rights and liberties of free coloured residents.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=195}}{{sfn|Bolland|1975|p=195}}{{sfn|Bolland|1977|pp=95–96}}<ref group=note>Possibly response to Saint Domingue revolt /v Bolland C 195 / Possibly see Hon letter 19 Dec 1791 re 203 French negroes on board ship Recovery and schooner Friendship, Capt Albro, in Mail or Claypoole's Daily Advertiser 257 2 = 26 Mar 1792 Link: https://infoweb-newsbank-com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/apps/readex/doc?p=EANX&docref=image/v2%3A10DBDEF6190C2BA0%40EANX-10DAA8C26FBF82C0%402375660-10DAA8C2AB394EC0%401-10DAA8C42EAFF338%40Honduras%252C%2BDec.%2B19%252C%2B1791 / NEW-YORK, Apr 7 [1792]. Two vessel loads of negroes and mulattoes, sent fm Port-au-prince to Hon, have since arrived at Jam; these wretches were banished fm Port-au-prince for having borne arms against the whites. The government of Jam, it is said, gave orders to have them sent to Cape Francois under an escort of two men of war, where they have since arrived. /Vermont Gazette 9 47 3 = 20 Apr 1792 / Possibly see Hon letter 26 Nov 1791 in Dunlap's American Daily Advertiser [PA] 4136 2 = 28 Apr 1792 Link: https://infoweb-newsbank-com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/apps/readex/doc?p=EANX&docref=image/v2%3A10380B3185E81D90%40EANX-1074B24DE456EEC8%402375693-1074B24EABA084A0%403-1074B2516719EEF8%40Foreign%2BIntelligence.%2BBriston%252C%2BMarch1 /// In order to prevent the many mischiefs that may hereafter arise form the wicked art of Negroes going under the appellation of Obeah Men and Women, pretending to have communication with the Devil and other evil Spirits, whereby the weak and superstitious are deluded into a Belief of their having full power to exempt them whilst under their protection from any Evils that might otherwise happen; It is hereby RESOLVED that any free person of Colour or Slave, who shall hereafter pretend to any supernatural Power in order to affect the Health or Lives of others, or extorting Money or Effects under false pretences, or any way compassing the Life of any person by such means, or otherwise advising aiding or abeting any Slave or Slaves to depart their Masters Service, or shall harbour any runaway Slaves, or promote the purposes of Rebellion, shall upon conviction thereof, suffer Death or such other punishment as the Magistrates and Jury shall think proper to direct. /v Burdon 1 195 /Laws 1810 /// From "Lights and Shadows of a Sailor's Life," published in the Edinburgh Observer. ... I journeyed up the river to Free-Town, ... In a little bamboo cottage, in the outskirts of Free-Town, dwelt ... an Acrimontee girl called Olive, that lived there with her mother, ... She [mother] was the sybil of the village, and made a sort of traffic of Obeah magic, that was sanctioned and encouraged by all the neighbourhood. Cattle-drivers bought her spells to counteract diseases in their herds, and logwood-hunters came ot have their eyes anointed, before setting out upon their journies of discovery; ..." /Antigua Weekly Register 14 714 4 = 1 Jan 1828 Link: https://infoweb-newsbank-com.ezp-prod1.hul.harvard.edu/apps/readex/doc?p=EANACN&docref=image/v2%3A145EB27AE90296CD%40EANACN-14CA6F77072CF5B8%402388723-14CA645BE067B720%403-14CA645BE067B720%40 /// 19 Nov 1816 Belize T. Arthur to Brathurst. Informs Andrew Fife, deserter fm 7th WIR, arrested for robbery and for wielding "so great [an] influence over the poor Slaves by virtue of his Obeah performances that the Country offered a public reward for his apprehension and after many extraordinary escapes he has been at length secured;" sent to court in Jam /CO 123/27 [Arthur to Brathurst 19 Nov 1816] /v Anderson M 348 /// [c 1850 Belize T.] Slaves' "masters and mistresses were ... drawn into the crimes of Obeahism" eg one "Miss Clarissa Parslow, a proprietress of land, houses, and slaves, who died about 1841" was believed to have practiced obeah /v Bolland F 96, 215 no 41 /Crowe 324</ref>

'''1792'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'': Spanish arrivals due to civil unrest or insurrection in neighbouring Spanish settlements./Carlisle Gazette [PA] 8 369 3 = 29 Aug 1792<ref group=note>PHILADELPHIA, Aug 25 [1792]. Capt Love of the schooner John, fm Jam, spoke an Eng ship off Capt St. Antonio, out eight days fm Hon, bound for Lon, the captain of which informed him, that an insurrection had broke out in the Sp settlements there; thatt he insurgents had murdered the Lt-Gov or Lt-Gen, (Capt Love is not certain which) and many other respectable characters! Several Sp had arrived at the Eng settlement, to which they had fled for security; and when they had left home there was every reason to apprehend that the disturbances would not soon be quelled. /Carlisle Gazette 8 369</ref>
* mid-February{{snd}}end of July: Juan Bautista Gual inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|pp=349, 389}}<ref group=note>Informe de Gual en Bacalar a 25 jul 1792. En el reconocimiento de la costa y cayos de Barlovento [bw Old and Bahía de la Ascensión], hallé entre estos, pescando fuera de límites, muchos súbditos ingleses a quienes decomisé la pesca, devolviéndoles sus buques y muebles y permitiéndoles regresar a los establecimientos apercibidos, con arreglo a las órdenes de que serían tratados con rigor en lo sucesivo ... Como para fines de Frebrero debía haber en la boca del Walix un Comisario Británico que me acompañase a la visita anterior de los establecimientos, ... pero encontrándome sin el Comisario, me pasé a Cayo Frixol, distante 3 leguas de dicha Boca a esperarlo. En el Cayo encontré un pescador establecido con su familia, y habiéndole hecho ver, que estaba cometiendo una infracción lo evacuó ... me trasladé el 15-3 a la Boca del Walix para practicar las diligencias que debían preceder al reconocimiento, y el 17 me informaron los Magistrados, que entre los papeles de Mr. Lorenze Meygham, que había fallecido a principios del mismo mes, habían encontrado un pliego de mi General para el de Jam, ... La operación de reconocer los huertas me proporcionó el ver perfectamente los establecimientos. En lo interior de ellos, no noté trangresión alguno de los que se recomiendan como graves en el Tratado ... y Convención ... Esto es obra de defensa u otras militares de artillería, o tropa, pero sí excesos en el cultivo, ... pero es de advertir, que dichos excesos son bastante depreciables para el que las vea; porque las huertas tan pretendidas no son otra cosa en lo general, que unos plantales, muchos de ellos mal cuidados, que tienen por objeto, no la delicadeza, sino el ahorro de víveres para los negros, pues no ví ni aun una lechuga en todos los establecimientos; bien que no por esto dejé de explicarme como debía, acerca de excederse en cuanto al terreno, y en lo tocante a las plantas de cultivo, considerando que cuando se tolera y disimula lo poco, lleguen los abusos a lo sumo; ... mi correspondencia con los Magistrados, aunque siempre los nombré con este título, fué solamente como unos sujetos particulares visibles; ... tuve el designio de no consentir en el sistema de policía que observan, por ser materia dudosa, aun entre ellos ... si S.M.B. puede, sin la anuencia de nuestro Soberano, disponer la observancia de dicho sistema ... En nlas riberas extra límites del Valis, su brazo y los esteros Black Crek y Spanish Crek, noté muchos y graves infracciones. Estas fueron el cultivo de varios pedazos de terreno, una considerable porción estraída de palo de Campeachy y de mora, y como 700 árboles de caoba cortados, y sacados ... De éstos y de la cantidad de caoba extraída, no hubiera yo podido instruirme con toda exactitud, si no me hubiera auxiliado a ellos las noticias de habitantes fidedignos, las cuales no me fué difícil adquirir, porque el común de los habitantes detesta semejantes infracciones, y anhela el verlas remediadas, por lo que le dañan, haciendo descender el precio de la caoba con la excesiva abundancia a la mitad de lo que generalmente se considera necesario para que la corta sea útil a los cortadores. ... Los más de los pescadores de los establecimientos; hacen la pesca, especialmente la de la tortuga fuera de límites; entre los cayos que están al sur de los mismos establecimientos, y uno, y otro he oído que van a las islas inmediatas al Cabo Catoche ... No hay, como he dicho, en los establecimientos, obra alguno de defensa, ni el menos preparativo militar, pues de dos casas fuertes, que cuando yo salí para la visita, aún se dudaba si existían en la Boca de Jalova, no había en ésta ni señales de donde estuvieron, pero me hallo bien enterado de que el Oficial a quien se comisionó, para examinar el estado de las costas durante los últimos recelos de rompimiento, no padeció ni la más level equivocación en cuanto informó tocante a obras, a ejercicios militares, que quiso desfigurar el Sup Hunter; ... hay 9 Magistrados, de que bastan 3 para formar un cuerpo; transan las desavenencias civiles que ocurren entre los habitantes, y juzgan los delitos cometidos dentro de los límites, con autoridad de condenar a muerte, y hacer ejecutar la pena, fundando sus sentencias sobre las leyes generales de Inglaterra. Su oficio es anual, y se eligen los nuevos a principios de Mayo. Hay también otro cuerpo político que se titula el Gran Jury, y se compone de 12 habitantes juramentados cuya obligación es representar a los Magistrados en Juntas Generales, que se celebran cada 3 meses, todo lo que es necesario a favor del común. Así me explicó un Magistrado, persona de talento y verdad, dicho sistema. No hay Superintendente, ni esperan que la haya; .. /v Calderon 389 /MEXICO,3025</ref>
* 31 August{{snd}}31 August: James Dundas Yarborough, on request of the Bench of Magistrates, grants Belize a portion of his land for use as a burying ground.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|pp=194, 200}}<ref group=note>1791, August 31st. Quarterly Court with Grand Jury. Reprobation by Grand Jury of the indecent appearance of the Public Burial Ground and recommendation for obtaning from Captain Yarborough part of his plantation for a Public Burial Ground with provision of space for those not entitled to Church Rites. /v Burdon 1 194 /GC F /// 1792, August 31st. Quarterly Court. ... recommended immediate opening of a new burial ground presented to the pubic by ames D. Yarborough Esq., and the closing of the old place of interment. /v Burdon 1 200 /GC F</ref>

'''1793'''
* start of March{{snd}}end of December: José Alvarez inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary.{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|p=351}}

'''1794'''
* 1 March{{snd}}1 March: Magistrates run a print notice regarding the death of William Penn, possibly marking the first print notice by Magistrates (as opposed to notices posted around Belize, [[Barcadares]] or [[St. George's Caye|St. George's]]).{{sfn|DAD|1794|p=3|loc=iss. no. 4774}}<ref group=note>Earlier instances possibly in print publications from Kingston or Spanish T publishers / Though see Lon publications by Robert White eg White H</ref>
* 28 August{{snd}}5 September: Magistrates establish a market for Belize, on recommendation by a grand jury to the [[Quarterly Court]].{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=211}}<ref group=note>5 Sep 1794 Quarterly Ct. High Constable and Clerk of Market appointed at £15 Jam Currency per quarter /v Burdon 1 /MM A1</ref>
* 5 September{{snd}}5 September: Magistrates appoint a High Constable for Belize, remunerated at 15 Jamaican pounds per quarter, charged with removing nuisances and reporting offenders.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=211}}
* 5 September{{snd}}5 September: The Public Treasurer is directed to prosecute his predecessor £500, which had been misused or misappropriated from the Public Treasury.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=211}}<ref group=note>5 Sep 1794. Quarterly Court. Public Treasurer directed to commence a Prosecution for £500 cash for a Settlement of the late Treasurer's accounts.{{harv|Burdon|1931|p=211}}</ref>
* 12 September{{snd}}12 September: Public Treasury is confirmed as an office without the Bench of Magistrates.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=211}}

'''1795'''
* 24 April{{snd}}24 April: [[First West India Regiment]] is commissioned.<ref group=note>24 Apr—1 Sep 1795 Eight WIR commissioned, inc incorporation of Carolina Corps, est 1779, to 1st WIR /xxx /// Possibly see A. B. Ellis, *The History of the First West India Regiment* [Lon, Chapman and Hall, 1885] /// See Roger N. Buckley, *Slaves in Redcoats: The British West India Regiments, 1795–1815* [New Haven, Yale University Press, 1979] /v Anderson M 350 fn 102</ref>
* 1 August{{snd}}end of March of 1796: [[Second Maroon War]].

'''1796'''
* start of March{{snd}}end of August: Juan O'Sullivan inspects the English settlement as Spanish commissary.{{sfn|F|1849|pp=???|loc=iss. nos. 48—51 dated 25 June–??? 1849}}{{sfn|Peniche|1869|pp=256, 377–???}}{{sfn|Calderón Quijano|1944|p=352}}<ref group=note>En ellos [documentos de la visita] encontramos ... que los colonos [ingléses] abusaban del territorio que les estaba concedido, y dejaban de pagar los derechos por las licencias que obtanian [del comisario]. ... dice O'Sullivan que llamaban magistrados á algunos principales, que sin duda serian los mas ricos, estos mismos le dijeron, cuando los requirió para que obligasen á pagar á otros colonos que adeudaban de derechos [licences], que no tenian autoridad alguna sobre los demas. ... [O'Sullivan] apresó varias armas de fuego á los pescadores y aun les decomisó la pesca que habian hecho fuera de los límites concedidos al efecto, .../v Peniche 256, 377 /// [En Informe de O'Sullivan] se notaba la tendencia á independerse y aprovecharse del territorio como propio, burlando el pago de los derechos, debido á la falta de concurrencia del comisario inglés, ... /v Peniche 879 /// 1796 Last Sp Commissary inspection /v Bolland F 58</ref>
* 7 December{{snd}}7 December: The Governor of Jamaica appoints Thomas Barrow Superintendent, purportedly without instruction from Whitehall, on receiving complaints from the Spanish commissary Juan O’Sullivan regarding the disorderly state of the English settlement, and the unbecoming behaviour of James Guerin (sailor in a corvette in port during the Spanish inspection).{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=222}}

'''1797'''
* 11 April{{snd}}1 May: The Royal Navy (forcibly) resettle Garifuna residents of [[St. Vincent]] (and some which had prior been detained in Truxillo) in Roatan.{{sfn|GG|1797|p=???|loc=iss. no. ??? dated 26 June 1797}}{{sfn|Taylor|2012|pp=157–164}}{{sfn|Luján Muñoz|2005a|pp=401–403}}{{sfn|Palma Ramos|1974|p=Palma 47}}{{sfn|Gonzalez|1983|pp=143–149}}<ref group=note>1795–1797 St. Vincent. Second Carib War / Feb 1797 St Vincent. Deportation of c 2,600 Caribs begins / 12 Apr 1797 Rattan. First Carib = Garifuna deportees arrive / Oct 1797 Sp encounter c 1,800 Garifuna inc 31 Caciques in Rattan, and resettle or remove them to Truxillo /v Lujan 3 401–402 /// 1796 Truxillo. > 300 Haitians fm St Dominge brought /v Palma 31 /AGCA A2.5 exp 6867 leg 301 /AGCA A2.5.1 exp 6775 leg 300 /// 1797 Omoa, Truxillo. > 5,000 Garifuna fm Roatan relocated to Omoa, and 289 to Truxillo /v Palma 31 /AGCA A2.1 exp 3269 leg 120 f 1 /// 21 Jul 1796 – 2 Feb 1797 St Vincent. 4,195 Garifuna, 41 slaves, 102 Caribs evacuated to Baliseau /WO 1/82 f 645 / 12 Apr–1 May 1797 Roatan. 664 men, 1,362 women and children = 2,026 total Garifuna landed at Roatan fm Baliseau, after sm Sp garrison there surrendered, after which Sp captives are taken to Truxillo to be exchanged for 300 Garifuna and crew of a transport which had been seized by Sp en route fm Jam to Roatan, during which exchange Truxillo is shelled /Gaceta de Guatemala xxx = 26 Jun 1797 /WO 52/2976 / 23 Sep 1797 Truxillo. Sp evacuate 1,465 Garifuna fm Roatan / 16 Oct 1797 Roatan. 206 Garifuna still left in Roatan /AGCA A3.16 exp 2025 leg 194 /WO 1/799 f 759 /WO 1/82 f 719 /v Gonzalez 147–149, 165–166 no 6–9 /// 18–19 May 1797 Roatan. Garifuna ally with or surrender to Sp /v Gonzalez 150, 166 no 11 /v Burdon 1 233</ref>
* 30 May{{snd}}30 May: Thomas Graham, charged with the clandestine logging of mahogany 'using finesse and deception,' faces an irregularly-constituted Court of Auditors (of five auditors, as opposed to thirteen), which he protests.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=228}}<ref group=note>Apparently Public Meeting had previously acceded to a court of five auditors, perhaps while under martial law /v Burdon 1 230 /MMA 2 [1 Jun 1797]</ref>

'''1798'''
* 19 January{{snd}}19 January: Public Treasurer (mis-)appropriates £150 from the Treasury, on account of the same amount's having been stolen from his private funds.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=243}}<ref group=note>1798, January 19th. Public Meetnig, 38 present. ... Resolved that a summons be issued against the Public Treasurer for £150, being a deficiency in his credits, withheld by him as a reimbursement for that amount stolen from him. /v Burdon 1 243 /MM A2 /// 1799, August 29th. Magistrates' Meeting. ... Treasurer directed to give the Police Magistrate a statement of the funds on the first Monday of each month. /v Burdon 1 273 /MM A2</ref>

'''1799'''
* ''s.d.''{{snd}}''s.d.'' of 1800: English logging extends south of the [[Sibun River]].{{sfn|Gonzalez|1983|p=152}}{{sfn|Bolland|1977|p=31}}<ref group=note>Though see lossy 1777 Washington Affair re Sherboon R /// ≤ 1799 Deep R logging begun / ≤ 1809 Stand Creek = important settlement "from whence considerable quantities of wood has been shipped, and HM Ships that come to Hon generally water there" /CO 123/18 [Barrow Remarks 1 May 1809] / ≤ 1806 Grande R [N of PG] logging begun /v Burdon 2 92 / ≤ 1814 Moho R [S of PG] settled /CO 123/23 [Smyth to Bathurst 24 May 1814] /v Burdon 2 167 / ≤ 1824 Sarstoon R settled or logging begun /v Humphreys 18 /FO 15/4 [Horton to Planta 23 Sep 1825] /v Bolland F 31</ref>
* 10 April{{snd}}end of April: ''Daley'' and other officers of the [[Sixth West India Regiment]] commit a 'violent outrage' on the Magistrates, including threatening to turn them out of the Court House so as to use it as a guard house, 'as if the Military had a proprietary right to [the Court House], instead of merely being allowed to use it by permission of the Magistrates,' whereupon the Magistrates threaten to resign, which stalemate is eventually resolved by the Superintendent in favour of the Magistrates.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=268}}
* 9 May{{snd}}9 May: On account of each candidate to the Bench of Magistrates's having garnered only one vote in the polls, the Superintendent is asked to and does appoint seven Magistrates, likely marking the first time the Bench is appointed (rather than elected).{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=270}}
* 26 June{{snd}}26 June: The [[Governor of Jamaica]] pardons a midshipman of {{HMS|Merlin|1796|6}}, who had been sentenced to death by the [[Grand Court]] of Belize on being found guilty of having forged John Ralph Moss's handwriting, (possibly) marking the first use of the [[royal prerogative of mercy]] in the English settlement.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=272}}
* 16 July{{snd}}16 July: The Public Meeting honours John Ralph Moss for his defence of the settlement aboard the {{HMS|Merlin|1796|6}} during the [[Battle of St. George's Caye]], gifting him a sword valued at 100 [[Guinea (coin)|guineas]], this (possibly) being the first honours granted by the English settlement.{{sfn|Burdon|1931|p=273}}

